WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:02.180
It starts before you even get out of bed, doesn't it?

00:02.200 --> 00:04.100
Oh, yeah. For me, it's the alarm.

00:04.580 --> 00:07.680
You turn off your alarm, your eyes are barely open,

00:08.060 --> 00:09.680
you're still warm under the covers,

00:09.920 --> 00:11.480
and your thumb just...

00:11.480 --> 00:15.160
It instinctively drifts to that app.

00:16.300 --> 00:17.420
You know the one.

00:17.640 --> 00:19.720
You know the one, and you know you shouldn't.

00:19.780 --> 00:20.560
You know you shouldn't.

00:20.680 --> 00:23.480
And before your brain has even fully booted up,

00:23.800 --> 00:24.660
you're seeing it.

00:24.740 --> 00:25.800
The wall of text.

00:26.040 --> 00:27.100
The wall of screaming.

00:27.200 --> 00:28.800
It's not just information, is it?

00:28.800 --> 00:31.200
It's this senator is a traitor,

00:31.460 --> 00:34.060
or this director is a moral monster.

00:34.260 --> 00:37.360
The ice caps are melting faster than we thought,

00:38.160 --> 00:39.580
which is probably true,

00:39.720 --> 00:41.080
but then right next to it is

00:41.080 --> 00:44.600
this specific coffee shop is problematic.

00:45.040 --> 00:46.200
It's a sensory assault.

00:46.560 --> 00:48.100
It feels like a physical thing.

00:48.180 --> 00:48.620
It is.

00:48.680 --> 00:51.160
It's the defining sensation of the modern Internet.

00:51.520 --> 00:55.220
It's an immediate high-stakes spike in cortisol

00:55.220 --> 00:56.960
before you've even had coffee.

00:57.420 --> 00:57.940
Exactly.

00:57.940 --> 00:59.540
It's like walking into a room,

01:00.040 --> 01:00.500
I don't know,

01:00.680 --> 01:01.800
maybe a hospital ward,

01:01.980 --> 01:03.820
or a stock exchange floor,

01:04.040 --> 01:06.400
where every single machine

01:06.400 --> 01:08.260
and every single person

01:08.260 --> 01:10.280
is screaming at the top of their lungs.

01:10.460 --> 01:11.520
That's a great analogy.

01:12.080 --> 01:12.880
And the thing is,

01:13.320 --> 01:14.500
usually they aren't.

01:15.620 --> 01:16.360
They aren't wrong.

01:16.940 --> 01:17.860
That's the catch.

01:17.960 --> 01:18.140
Right.

01:18.240 --> 01:19.600
That's the insidious part.

01:19.720 --> 01:20.840
The things they're mad about,

01:21.380 --> 01:22.180
they are real,

01:22.580 --> 01:23.760
the climate is changing,

01:24.120 --> 01:26.260
that politician might actually be terrible.

01:26.260 --> 01:28.500
The signals aren't necessarily false.

01:28.720 --> 01:32.280
The content of the scream is often factually correct.

01:32.440 --> 01:35.220
But I've noticed something really disturbing in myself lately.

01:36.160 --> 01:38.860
And I'm almost a blurriness to say it.

01:38.980 --> 01:39.780
I'm exhausted.

01:40.080 --> 01:41.020
I think everyone is.

01:41.560 --> 01:43.440
And worse than being exhausted,

01:44.180 --> 01:46.960
I feel like I'm stopping to listen.

01:46.960 --> 01:49.400
Like, I see a headline that says,

01:49.500 --> 01:50.480
Ultimate Disaster,

01:50.580 --> 01:50.940
and I just,

01:51.340 --> 01:52.220
I keep scrolling.

01:52.300 --> 01:53.900
The thumb just keeps moving.

01:54.020 --> 01:55.460
And I feel like I'm becoming numb.

01:55.820 --> 01:58.340
And I start to worry that that means I'm a bad person,

01:58.460 --> 01:58.960
or I'm apathetic,

01:59.600 --> 02:00.120
or I've just,

02:00.480 --> 02:00.840
you know,

02:00.900 --> 02:02.420
lost my capacity for empathy.

02:02.500 --> 02:03.440
You aren't apathetic,

02:03.560 --> 02:04.420
you're habituated.

02:04.960 --> 02:05.400
Habituated.

02:05.540 --> 02:07.260
And that is precisely the tension

02:07.260 --> 02:08.740
we are grappling with today.

02:08.980 --> 02:10.480
We are living in an environment

02:10.480 --> 02:12.520
of constant alarm signals,

02:12.520 --> 02:15.020
but the central question we need to ask,

02:15.080 --> 02:16.220
and this is a question about,

02:16.300 --> 02:16.600
like,

02:17.200 --> 02:18.720
the physics of information

02:18.720 --> 02:20.100
as much as it is about politics,

02:20.440 --> 02:21.240
is this.

02:21.580 --> 02:24.460
What happens when the alarm never stops ringing?

02:24.620 --> 02:26.000
Does it stop being an alarm?

02:26.140 --> 02:28.900
Does it just become background radiation?

02:29.340 --> 02:30.160
And more importantly,

02:30.280 --> 02:31.740
does keeping that alarm ringing

02:31.740 --> 02:33.340
actually make us worse

02:33.340 --> 02:34.800
at fixing the problems?

02:35.040 --> 02:35.440
Ah,

02:35.520 --> 02:36.680
now that's the core of it.

02:36.940 --> 02:37.340
Because

02:37.340 --> 02:39.340
if I'm ignoring the fire alarm

02:39.340 --> 02:41.600
because it's been ringing for 10 years straight,

02:41.600 --> 02:43.060
what happens

02:43.060 --> 02:44.080
when there's an actual,

02:44.460 --> 02:44.780
you know,

02:44.900 --> 02:45.920
in my kitchen fire?

02:46.240 --> 02:47.560
That is the question.

02:47.680 --> 02:48.920
So to help us answer that,

02:49.220 --> 02:50.780
we're doing a deep dive

02:50.780 --> 02:52.120
into a brand new

02:52.120 --> 02:52.880
and honestly

02:52.880 --> 02:54.220
a really fascinating

02:54.220 --> 02:55.040
piece of writing.

02:55.240 --> 02:56.560
It's an essay titled

02:56.560 --> 02:57.780
The Polemic Debt,

02:58.340 --> 02:59.480
Critical Momentum,

02:59.620 --> 03:01.100
and the Cognitive Economics

03:01.100 --> 03:02.020
of Refutation.

03:02.260 --> 03:03.020
It's a mouthful.

03:03.400 --> 03:04.060
It's by an author

03:04.060 --> 03:04.760
known as Fliction,

03:05.340 --> 03:05.960
and it's dated

03:05.960 --> 03:07.000
just a couple of days ago,

03:07.000 --> 03:08.000
February 17,

03:08.260 --> 03:09.080
2026.

03:09.260 --> 03:09.900
Very fresh.

03:10.800 --> 03:11.500
And I have to say,

03:11.600 --> 03:12.800
this source material

03:12.800 --> 03:14.920
is ambitious.

03:15.520 --> 03:16.920
It's a bit of a rollercoaster.

03:17.060 --> 03:17.260
I mean,

03:17.280 --> 03:18.520
it starts out talking about

03:18.520 --> 03:19.620
rhetorical theory

03:19.620 --> 03:20.580
and how we argue.

03:20.700 --> 03:20.940
Hmm,

03:21.080 --> 03:22.400
pretty standard stuff so far.

03:22.560 --> 03:24.300
Then it takes a hard left turn

03:24.300 --> 03:25.820
into cognitive science

03:25.820 --> 03:26.820
and brain chemistry,

03:27.540 --> 03:28.740
literally talking about

03:28.740 --> 03:29.680
metabolic energy.

03:29.940 --> 03:30.840
Which is where I really

03:30.840 --> 03:31.800
started to lean in.

03:32.120 --> 03:32.620
And then,

03:33.280 --> 03:34.160
and this is the part

03:34.160 --> 03:35.440
that really threw me

03:35.440 --> 03:36.060
for a loop.

03:36.060 --> 03:38.780
It ends up being

03:38.780 --> 03:40.180
a passionate defense

03:40.180 --> 03:42.940
of 1970s software tools.

03:42.940 --> 03:43.640
It sounds like

03:43.640 --> 03:44.520
a strange mix,

03:44.620 --> 03:44.960
I know.

03:45.640 --> 03:46.280
You wouldn't think

03:46.280 --> 03:47.080
text editors

03:47.080 --> 03:48.260
and moral outrage

03:48.260 --> 03:49.740
belong in the same conversation.

03:50.000 --> 03:50.560
Not at all.

03:50.700 --> 03:51.260
But the connection

03:51.260 --> 03:52.620
is actually incredibly tight.

03:53.200 --> 03:54.280
The author is connecting

03:54.280 --> 03:55.300
how we speak

03:55.300 --> 03:56.320
to how we think

03:56.320 --> 03:57.260
and finally

03:57.260 --> 03:58.460
to the tools we use

03:58.460 --> 03:59.500
to do that thinking.

03:59.700 --> 04:00.600
It connects Vim,

04:00.840 --> 04:01.620
the code editor,

04:02.180 --> 04:02.840
to the concept

04:02.840 --> 04:04.060
of polemic debt.

04:04.240 --> 04:05.020
Which is a sentence

04:05.020 --> 04:05.920
you never thought

04:05.920 --> 04:06.440
you'd say.

04:06.500 --> 04:06.780
Ever.

04:07.400 --> 04:08.060
But it works.

04:08.220 --> 04:08.880
It really does.

04:08.900 --> 04:10.740
It's surprisingly coherent.

04:11.420 --> 04:12.340
So let's set the mission

04:12.340 --> 04:13.140
for this deep dive.

04:13.480 --> 04:14.540
We are going to unpack

04:14.540 --> 04:15.420
this concept

04:15.420 --> 04:16.500
of polemic debt.

04:17.320 --> 04:18.600
The basic idea

04:18.600 --> 04:19.960
is that by overusing

04:19.960 --> 04:21.020
extreme critique,

04:21.660 --> 04:23.000
by constantly turning

04:23.000 --> 04:24.000
the dial to 11,

04:24.580 --> 04:25.700
we are accumulating

04:25.700 --> 04:26.700
a kind of debt.

04:26.860 --> 04:27.700
We are borrowing

04:27.700 --> 04:29.700
against our future credibility

04:29.700 --> 04:30.980
and our future energy.

04:31.140 --> 04:31.680
And eventually

04:31.680 --> 04:32.720
the bill comes due.

04:32.840 --> 04:34.260
The bill always comes due.

04:34.360 --> 04:34.800
Exactly.

04:35.140 --> 04:36.080
So we're going to split

04:36.080 --> 04:36.700
this discussion

04:36.700 --> 04:37.920
into two main parts,

04:38.060 --> 04:39.500
just like the source material does.

04:40.040 --> 04:40.960
First, we're going to look

04:40.960 --> 04:41.860
at the human side,

04:42.340 --> 04:42.940
the rhetoric,

04:43.400 --> 04:44.220
the outrage,

04:44.580 --> 04:45.800
and how that bankrupts

04:45.800 --> 04:46.340
our attention.

04:46.620 --> 04:47.900
The psychology of it all.

04:48.280 --> 04:49.000
Then we're going to pivot

04:49.000 --> 04:50.180
to the technical side,

04:50.660 --> 04:51.920
how our apps

04:51.920 --> 04:52.900
and digital tools

04:52.900 --> 04:53.780
are trapping us

04:53.780 --> 04:54.780
in the same cycle

04:54.780 --> 04:55.420
of exhaustion,

04:55.860 --> 04:57.180
and why the solution

04:57.180 --> 04:57.940
might be,

04:58.440 --> 04:59.180
well,

04:59.700 --> 05:00.700
a bit retro.

05:00.880 --> 05:01.860
It's going to be a journey

05:01.860 --> 05:02.840
from the abstract

05:02.840 --> 05:03.860
to the very,

05:03.980 --> 05:04.740
very concrete.

05:04.940 --> 05:05.660
Okay, let's do it.

05:05.720 --> 05:06.380
So part one,

05:07.420 --> 05:07.980
the mechanics

05:07.980 --> 05:09.120
of signal decay.

05:09.880 --> 05:10.860
The essay starts

05:10.860 --> 05:12.240
by defining polemic.

05:12.440 --> 05:12.820
Right.

05:13.140 --> 05:13.940
Now, usually

05:13.940 --> 05:14.960
when I hear that word,

05:15.000 --> 05:16.320
I think of a really

05:16.320 --> 05:16.920
aggressive,

05:17.320 --> 05:18.180
angry speech,

05:18.980 --> 05:19.700
a rant,

05:20.080 --> 05:21.100
a manifesto.

05:21.100 --> 05:22.240
That's the common usage

05:22.240 --> 05:22.760
for sure.

05:23.120 --> 05:24.220
We think of polemic

05:24.220 --> 05:25.040
as an emotion.

05:25.600 --> 05:26.900
He was being polemical,

05:27.040 --> 05:27.800
meaning he was being

05:27.800 --> 05:28.680
mean or aggressive.

05:28.920 --> 05:29.420
Yeah, exactly.

05:29.740 --> 05:31.040
But the author here

05:31.040 --> 05:32.140
is asking us

05:32.140 --> 05:33.040
to look at polemic

05:33.040 --> 05:34.320
not as an emotion,

05:34.460 --> 05:37.480
but as a signaling technology.

05:37.560 --> 05:38.020
Technology.

05:38.220 --> 05:39.240
Okay, unpack that for me.

05:39.300 --> 05:39.560
Yes.

05:40.000 --> 05:40.500
Think about what

05:40.500 --> 05:41.500
a technology does.

05:41.600 --> 05:42.640
It serves a function.

05:42.800 --> 05:44.060
The function of polemic

05:44.060 --> 05:44.940
is to interrupt

05:44.940 --> 05:46.700
the normal flow of things.

05:46.780 --> 05:47.680
To break the pattern.

05:48.080 --> 05:48.560
Precisely.

05:48.560 --> 05:49.220
It's designed

05:49.220 --> 05:50.360
to signal urgency.

05:50.640 --> 05:51.680
If we are having

05:51.680 --> 05:52.860
a polite conversation

05:52.860 --> 05:53.900
about dinner plans

05:53.900 --> 05:55.440
and suddenly I scream,

05:55.940 --> 05:56.300
fire!

05:56.860 --> 05:57.080
Yeah.

05:57.160 --> 05:57.680
I have used

05:57.680 --> 05:58.560
a polemic signal.

05:58.840 --> 05:59.880
I have interrupted

05:59.880 --> 06:01.020
the flow to signal

06:01.020 --> 06:02.140
a structural threat.

06:02.480 --> 06:03.240
Okay, that makes sense.

06:03.340 --> 06:04.100
It's a flare gun.

06:04.300 --> 06:04.980
You don't fire

06:04.980 --> 06:05.620
to say hello.

06:05.720 --> 06:06.080
You don't.

06:06.180 --> 06:06.660
It's designed

06:06.660 --> 06:08.180
to stop everything else

06:08.180 --> 06:08.880
so we can focus

06:08.880 --> 06:09.500
on the danger.

06:09.720 --> 06:11.400
And for that fire

06:11.400 --> 06:13.100
signal to work,

06:13.160 --> 06:14.060
it relies on what

06:14.060 --> 06:14.780
the author calls

06:14.780 --> 06:16.280
a severity gradient.

06:16.720 --> 06:17.840
I loved this term.

06:17.840 --> 06:19.360
A severity gradient.

06:19.520 --> 06:20.360
Can we dig into that?

06:20.420 --> 06:20.820
Absolutely.

06:21.100 --> 06:22.900
Imagine a volume knob

06:22.900 --> 06:23.980
or, better yet,

06:24.140 --> 06:25.180
the essay's example

06:25.180 --> 06:26.060
of a library.

06:26.820 --> 06:27.620
In a library,

06:28.020 --> 06:29.200
the baseline volume

06:29.200 --> 06:30.180
is near zero.

06:30.360 --> 06:30.500
Right.

06:30.560 --> 06:31.080
It's quiet.

06:31.400 --> 06:32.160
People are whispering.

06:32.480 --> 06:33.300
Pages are turning.

06:33.720 --> 06:34.740
So, if someone

06:34.740 --> 06:35.680
stands up and shouts,

06:35.800 --> 06:36.080
hey!

06:36.580 --> 06:37.760
Everyone turns around.

06:38.280 --> 06:38.920
The difference

06:38.920 --> 06:39.640
in volume

06:39.640 --> 06:41.040
between the background noise

06:41.040 --> 06:41.680
and the signal

06:41.680 --> 06:42.640
is huge.

06:42.760 --> 06:44.160
It's a massive difference.

06:44.360 --> 06:45.380
That is a steep

06:45.380 --> 06:46.420
severity gradient.

06:46.420 --> 06:48.040
If you whispered fire

06:48.040 --> 06:49.180
in a library,

06:49.640 --> 06:50.640
people might hear you,

06:50.740 --> 06:51.300
but they might just

06:51.300 --> 06:52.500
look around confused.

06:52.880 --> 06:53.960
If you screamed it,

06:54.020 --> 06:54.520
they'd move.

06:54.620 --> 06:55.120
For sure.

06:55.340 --> 06:56.400
Now, compare that

06:56.400 --> 06:57.240
to a mosh pit

06:57.240 --> 06:58.460
at a heavy metal concert.

06:58.900 --> 06:59.980
The baseline volume

06:59.980 --> 07:01.120
is already at maximum.

07:01.340 --> 07:02.580
It's a wall of sound.

07:02.700 --> 07:02.920
Right.

07:03.120 --> 07:04.320
The floor is vibrating.

07:04.460 --> 07:06.000
If you scream fire

07:06.000 --> 07:07.740
in a mosh pit,

07:07.860 --> 07:08.980
does anyone hear you?

07:09.180 --> 07:09.560
No.

07:09.560 --> 07:11.500
Not a single person.

07:11.660 --> 07:12.160
They just think

07:12.160 --> 07:12.940
it's part of the song.

07:13.360 --> 07:13.840
Precisely.

07:14.660 --> 07:15.580
So, in a healthy

07:15.580 --> 07:16.860
communication system,

07:17.120 --> 07:18.100
a healthy discourse,

07:18.880 --> 07:20.080
routine disagreements

07:20.080 --> 07:21.540
happen at a low volume.

07:22.320 --> 07:23.120
I disagree with

07:23.120 --> 07:24.040
your choice of restaurant.

07:24.240 --> 07:24.900
That's a whisper.

07:25.120 --> 07:25.900
That's low volume.

07:26.080 --> 07:27.580
But structural threats,

07:27.960 --> 07:29.840
the building is burning down.

07:30.260 --> 07:31.580
That happens at high volume.

07:32.000 --> 07:33.280
The gradient allows you

07:33.280 --> 07:34.260
to know which is which.

07:34.340 --> 07:34.840
It allows you

07:34.840 --> 07:36.280
to prioritize your attention.

07:36.480 --> 07:37.280
But here's where

07:37.280 --> 07:38.840
the polemic debt comes in.

07:38.920 --> 07:39.280
Yeah.

07:39.280 --> 07:40.540
What happens in our

07:40.540 --> 07:41.880
current digital environment

07:41.880 --> 07:43.640
when, you know,

07:43.920 --> 07:45.220
high frequency critique

07:45.220 --> 07:46.700
becomes the default mode?

07:46.960 --> 07:48.040
The gradient collapses.

07:48.220 --> 07:49.500
We are in the mosh pit.

07:49.880 --> 07:50.640
All the time.

07:50.740 --> 07:51.560
We are in the mosh pit,

07:51.620 --> 07:52.600
but we're trying to have

07:52.600 --> 07:53.560
a conversation about

07:53.560 --> 07:55.120
tax policy or climate change.

07:55.620 --> 07:57.560
If a review of a bad

07:57.560 --> 07:58.420
Marvel movie

07:58.420 --> 07:59.880
uses the same

07:59.880 --> 08:00.980
apocalyptic language

08:00.980 --> 08:02.660
as a report on a genocide.

08:02.980 --> 08:03.740
Which it does.

08:03.820 --> 08:04.280
It does.

08:04.500 --> 08:06.220
If everything is the end,

08:06.440 --> 08:07.040
the worst,

08:07.160 --> 08:08.260
the ultimate betrayal,

08:08.260 --> 08:09.740
then there is no gradient.

08:10.220 --> 08:11.560
Everything is just noise.

08:11.880 --> 08:12.880
This is signal decay.

08:13.160 --> 08:13.640
Exactly.

08:13.980 --> 08:15.480
And this isn't just a metaphor,

08:15.760 --> 08:16.440
which is what I found

08:16.440 --> 08:17.080
so compelling.

08:17.280 --> 08:18.200
The source material

08:18.200 --> 08:19.560
references audience

08:19.560 --> 08:21.180
adaptation and habituation.

08:21.620 --> 08:22.460
This isn't just

08:22.460 --> 08:23.640
people being cynical.

08:24.040 --> 08:26.120
It is a physiological response.

08:26.500 --> 08:27.080
So it's happening

08:27.080 --> 08:27.880
in our brains,

08:28.120 --> 08:28.500
chemically.

08:28.680 --> 08:28.980
Yes.

08:29.640 --> 08:31.260
Your brain is designed

08:31.260 --> 08:32.540
to dampen its response

08:32.540 --> 08:33.620
to constant alarms.

08:33.980 --> 08:35.120
If you live next

08:35.120 --> 08:36.040
to a train station,

08:36.540 --> 08:37.060
eventually,

08:37.060 --> 08:38.220
your brain

08:38.220 --> 08:39.420
literally stops

08:39.420 --> 08:40.800
processing the sound

08:40.800 --> 08:41.480
of the train

08:41.480 --> 08:42.560
so that you can

08:42.560 --> 08:43.780
continue to function.

08:44.320 --> 08:45.020
It has to.

08:45.360 --> 08:46.740
Because if you stayed

08:46.740 --> 08:47.920
in a state of high alert

08:47.920 --> 08:49.400
every time a train went by,

08:49.800 --> 08:50.880
you'd burn out in a week.

08:51.400 --> 08:52.260
Your nervous system

08:52.260 --> 08:52.900
would be shot.

08:53.060 --> 08:54.160
You'd be a wreck.

08:54.540 --> 08:56.640
So when every tweet,

08:56.780 --> 08:57.340
every article,

08:57.520 --> 08:58.480
every video title

08:58.480 --> 08:59.440
is screaming

08:59.440 --> 09:00.440
or this is the end

09:00.440 --> 09:01.060
of democracy

09:01.060 --> 09:02.200
or the ultimate betrayal,

09:02.200 --> 09:06.040
the brain engages habituation.

09:06.160 --> 09:07.060
It starts filtering.

09:07.380 --> 09:08.760
It filters out the urgency.

09:09.220 --> 09:10.100
It starts to treat

09:10.100 --> 09:11.440
the scream as silence.

09:12.060 --> 09:13.560
So by trying to make

09:13.560 --> 09:14.680
everything sound urgent,

09:14.940 --> 09:16.300
we've actually made it

09:16.300 --> 09:17.520
impossible to convey

09:17.520 --> 09:18.440
urgency at all.

09:18.520 --> 09:19.600
We've devalued

09:19.600 --> 09:20.700
the currency of alarm.

09:20.780 --> 09:21.460
If everything is

09:21.460 --> 09:22.000
an emergency,

09:22.300 --> 09:22.900
nothing is.

09:22.960 --> 09:23.500
And that leads

09:23.500 --> 09:24.540
to the second problem

09:24.540 --> 09:25.600
the essay highlights,

09:25.800 --> 09:27.580
which is rhetorical enclosure.

09:28.360 --> 09:29.940
This is a fascinating concept.

09:30.140 --> 09:31.260
This one hit close to home.

09:31.560 --> 09:33.160
Explain rhetorical enclosure.

09:33.540 --> 09:35.000
So when a critic

09:35.000 --> 09:36.660
is constantly operating

09:36.660 --> 09:38.200
at that high decibel

09:38.200 --> 09:39.440
polemical level,

09:39.840 --> 09:42.080
the audience stops reacting

09:42.080 --> 09:42.880
to the idea

09:42.880 --> 09:44.380
and starts reacting

09:44.380 --> 09:45.200
to the person.

09:45.340 --> 09:46.560
Oh, I see this all the time.

09:46.660 --> 09:47.900
The argument becomes

09:47.900 --> 09:49.020
persona bound.

09:49.180 --> 09:49.440
It's like,

09:49.520 --> 09:51.180
oh, there goes angry Steve again,

09:51.440 --> 09:52.960
yelling about the zoning laws.

09:53.400 --> 09:53.920
Exactly.

09:54.520 --> 09:55.960
Even if Steve is right.

09:56.520 --> 09:57.300
Let's say Steve

09:57.300 --> 09:58.580
has found a genuine

09:58.580 --> 10:00.300
catastrophic error

10:00.300 --> 10:01.740
in the zoning laws

10:01.740 --> 10:02.920
that could cause

10:02.920 --> 10:04.320
a bridge to collapse.

10:04.460 --> 10:06.180
A real, actual danger.

10:06.440 --> 10:07.660
But because Steve

10:07.660 --> 10:09.380
has spent the last five years

10:09.380 --> 10:10.800
screaming about everything

10:10.800 --> 10:12.200
from coffee cups

10:12.200 --> 10:13.180
to parking meters

10:13.180 --> 10:14.400
to the font

10:14.400 --> 10:15.480
on a city sign.

10:15.500 --> 10:15.700
Right.

10:15.960 --> 10:17.140
Everything is a catastrophe

10:17.140 --> 10:17.860
for Steve.

10:18.040 --> 10:18.700
When he screams

10:18.700 --> 10:19.660
about the zoning law,

10:20.240 --> 10:21.420
nobody hears the beta

10:21.420 --> 10:22.200
about the bridge.

10:22.320 --> 10:22.920
They just hear

10:22.920 --> 10:24.220
Steve being Steve.

10:24.320 --> 10:25.320
And they roll their eyes

10:25.320 --> 10:26.000
and move on.

10:26.000 --> 10:26.880
The argument

10:26.880 --> 10:28.660
loses its portability.

10:29.340 --> 10:29.820
Portability.

10:29.940 --> 10:31.040
That's a great word for it.

10:31.120 --> 10:31.260
Yeah.

10:31.560 --> 10:32.820
Portability is crucial

10:32.820 --> 10:33.560
for ideas.

10:33.880 --> 10:34.760
You want an idea

10:34.760 --> 10:36.120
to be able to leave your head

10:36.120 --> 10:37.520
and enter someone else's head

10:37.520 --> 10:38.340
without carrying

10:38.340 --> 10:39.000
the baggage

10:39.000 --> 10:39.960
of your personality.

10:40.060 --> 10:40.700
You want the idea

10:40.700 --> 10:41.560
to stand on its own

10:41.560 --> 10:42.000
two feet.

10:42.360 --> 10:43.860
You want the zoning board

10:43.860 --> 10:45.660
to look at the engineering error,

10:46.160 --> 10:47.800
not at Steve's angry face.

10:48.940 --> 10:50.340
But polemic makes

10:50.340 --> 10:51.780
the argument sticky.

10:52.780 --> 10:53.660
It covers it

10:53.660 --> 10:55.160
in the slime of outrage.

10:55.400 --> 10:56.440
It's like the argument

10:56.440 --> 10:57.580
is trapped inside

10:57.580 --> 10:58.180
the wrapper

10:58.180 --> 10:59.340
of a person's anger.

11:00.480 --> 11:01.520
And because people

11:01.520 --> 11:02.920
don't like being yelled at,

11:03.280 --> 11:04.640
they reject the wrapper.

11:04.880 --> 11:05.500
And they throw

11:05.500 --> 11:06.660
the argument out with it,

11:07.080 --> 11:07.880
unexamined.

11:08.040 --> 11:09.900
And that is a massive loss

11:09.900 --> 11:10.800
for the ecosystem

11:10.800 --> 11:11.420
of ideas.

11:12.060 --> 11:13.420
It's a tragedy, really.

11:13.780 --> 11:14.780
We need arguments

11:14.780 --> 11:15.860
to be extractable.

11:16.220 --> 11:16.940
We need to be able

11:16.940 --> 11:18.280
to take the core truth

11:18.280 --> 11:18.920
of a critique

11:18.920 --> 11:19.980
and move it

11:19.980 --> 11:20.860
into a solution.

11:21.640 --> 11:22.640
But if the critique

11:22.640 --> 11:23.440
is welded

11:23.440 --> 11:24.480
to a specific

11:24.480 --> 11:25.560
angry persona,

11:25.860 --> 11:26.960
it becomes stuck.

11:27.360 --> 11:28.240
It becomes inert.

11:28.560 --> 11:29.520
It's just performance

11:29.520 --> 11:30.240
at that point.

11:30.740 --> 11:31.240
It's funny

11:31.240 --> 11:32.120
because the people

11:32.120 --> 11:32.680
doing this

11:32.680 --> 11:33.620
usually feel like

11:33.620 --> 11:34.080
they're doing

11:34.080 --> 11:34.900
the most work.

11:35.300 --> 11:35.820
They feel like

11:35.820 --> 11:36.900
they're the only ones awake,

11:37.000 --> 11:37.660
the only ones yelling

11:37.660 --> 11:38.380
about the fire.

11:38.480 --> 11:39.260
They see themselves

11:39.260 --> 11:41.000
as the last honest person

11:41.000 --> 11:41.540
in the world.

11:41.700 --> 11:42.800
But the essay argues

11:42.800 --> 11:43.500
they're actually

11:43.500 --> 11:45.740
damaging the alarm system itself.

11:45.880 --> 11:46.900
They're cutting the wires

11:46.900 --> 11:47.560
while screaming

11:47.560 --> 11:48.360
into the microphone.

11:48.360 --> 11:49.500
They are depleting

11:49.500 --> 11:50.980
the resource of ragency.

11:51.780 --> 11:53.460
Urgency is a finite resource.

11:53.920 --> 11:55.120
You cannot manufacture

11:55.120 --> 11:56.000
infinite urgency.

11:56.400 --> 11:57.300
We are operating

11:57.300 --> 11:58.600
in an urgency deficit.

11:58.900 --> 12:00.360
Man, that is a heavy thought.

12:00.660 --> 12:02.560
Urgency is a finite resource.

12:02.960 --> 12:04.120
So this leads us

12:04.120 --> 12:04.980
into the second part

12:04.980 --> 12:05.620
of the discussion,

12:05.820 --> 12:07.600
which is the cognitive economics

12:07.600 --> 12:08.420
of all this.

12:08.480 --> 12:08.740
Right, right.

12:08.840 --> 12:10.200
Because it's not just

12:10.200 --> 12:11.180
about the arguments

12:11.180 --> 12:12.700
failing in the public square.

12:13.000 --> 12:15.020
It's about what this is doing

12:15.020 --> 12:16.360
to our actual brains.

12:16.360 --> 12:18.580
The cognitive toll

12:18.580 --> 12:20.400
of ambient polemic.

12:20.720 --> 12:21.720
The author brings up

12:21.720 --> 12:23.440
dual process theory Kahneman,

12:23.920 --> 12:26.040
thinking fast and slow.

12:26.760 --> 12:28.060
Now, I've heard of this,

12:28.260 --> 12:29.040
but help me understand

12:29.040 --> 12:29.680
how it applies

12:29.680 --> 12:30.540
to my Twitter feed.

12:30.740 --> 12:32.000
It's a classic framework,

12:32.260 --> 12:33.500
but the application here

12:33.500 --> 12:34.140
is novel.

12:34.380 --> 12:36.460
So Kahneman divides thinking

12:36.460 --> 12:37.420
into two systems.

12:37.920 --> 12:39.760
System one is fast,

12:40.020 --> 12:40.740
instinctive,

12:40.860 --> 12:41.640
and threat-oriented.

12:41.640 --> 12:42.540
Gut reaction.

12:42.920 --> 12:43.360
Exactly.

12:43.580 --> 12:44.640
It's what makes you jump

12:44.640 --> 12:45.660
when you see a stick

12:45.660 --> 12:46.700
that looks like a snake.

12:46.960 --> 12:47.860
It's what makes you slam

12:47.860 --> 12:48.980
on the brakes in traffic.

12:49.140 --> 12:50.060
It's very low energy.

12:50.260 --> 12:51.020
It's survival mode.

12:51.200 --> 12:51.420
Right.

12:51.860 --> 12:53.260
System two is slow,

12:53.620 --> 12:54.160
deliberative,

12:54.240 --> 12:54.920
and logical.

12:55.340 --> 12:56.420
It's what you use

12:56.420 --> 12:57.440
to do long division

12:57.440 --> 12:58.660
or plan a vacation

12:58.660 --> 13:00.140
or debug code.

13:00.140 --> 13:02.080
It is very energy intensive.

13:02.840 --> 13:03.420
Okay, so you've got

13:03.420 --> 13:04.200
the fast brain

13:04.200 --> 13:05.280
and the slow brain.

13:05.460 --> 13:06.300
And the argument here

13:06.300 --> 13:07.240
is that polemic

13:07.240 --> 13:08.540
keeps us locked

13:08.540 --> 13:09.580
in system one.

13:09.900 --> 13:10.180
Permanently.

13:10.180 --> 13:11.680
It feels like it.

13:12.240 --> 13:13.300
Polemic is designed

13:13.300 --> 13:15.300
to trigger a threat response.

13:16.040 --> 13:17.700
It hacks system one.

13:18.280 --> 13:19.460
So if you are constantly

13:19.460 --> 13:20.220
scrolling through

13:20.220 --> 13:21.180
a feed of outrage,

13:21.540 --> 13:22.640
you're keeping your brain

13:22.640 --> 13:23.580
in a state of

13:23.580 --> 13:25.380
high alert threat detection.

13:25.800 --> 13:27.180
Your amygdala is firing.

13:27.420 --> 13:28.600
Your cortisol is up.

13:29.340 --> 13:30.180
You're physically

13:30.180 --> 13:31.520
in a state of stress.

13:31.900 --> 13:32.420
You are.

13:32.740 --> 13:33.700
Your body is preparing

13:33.700 --> 13:34.460
for a confrontation.

13:35.140 --> 13:36.380
And here's the kicker,

13:36.480 --> 13:37.100
which you probably

13:37.100 --> 13:37.700
already know.

13:37.780 --> 13:38.840
You can't do long division

13:38.840 --> 13:39.380
while you're running

13:39.380 --> 13:39.900
from a bear.

13:40.180 --> 13:40.740
Precisely.

13:41.160 --> 13:42.360
This is the physiological

13:42.360 --> 13:43.340
reality.

13:43.600 --> 13:44.780
Sustained system one

13:44.780 --> 13:46.500
activation literally

13:46.500 --> 13:47.900
blocks system two.

13:48.640 --> 13:49.720
Your body shunts

13:49.720 --> 13:50.660
energy away

13:50.660 --> 13:52.000
from the prefrontal cortex,

13:52.140 --> 13:52.660
the part of you

13:52.660 --> 13:53.520
that thinks deeply

13:53.520 --> 13:55.240
and sends it to your muscles

13:55.240 --> 13:56.400
and your sensory organs.

13:56.680 --> 13:57.940
It's a zero-sum game

13:57.940 --> 13:59.000
with your body's energy.

13:59.240 --> 13:59.800
It is.

14:00.220 --> 14:01.440
You cannot engage

14:01.440 --> 14:03.360
in deep, nuanced reasoning

14:03.360 --> 14:05.000
when your biochemistry

14:05.000 --> 14:05.980
is screaming

14:05.980 --> 14:07.700
that you are under attack.

14:07.700 --> 14:08.700
So when we say

14:08.700 --> 14:09.700
online discourse

14:09.700 --> 14:10.360
is stupid

14:10.360 --> 14:11.560
or that people

14:11.560 --> 14:12.200
are reacting

14:12.200 --> 14:12.900
without thinking,

14:13.100 --> 14:14.420
we aren't just being mean.

14:14.620 --> 14:15.400
We are describing

14:15.400 --> 14:16.780
a biological state.

14:17.020 --> 14:17.520
We're making

14:17.520 --> 14:18.860
a clinical observation.

14:19.360 --> 14:20.320
We have chemically

14:20.320 --> 14:21.560
lobotomized ourselves

14:21.560 --> 14:22.200
with anger.

14:22.360 --> 14:23.740
That is a vivid way

14:23.740 --> 14:24.340
to put it.

14:24.480 --> 14:25.100
But yes,

14:25.300 --> 14:28.080
we are inducing

14:28.080 --> 14:29.600
a state of cognitive

14:29.600 --> 14:31.020
impairment in ourselves

14:31.020 --> 14:31.840
and others

14:31.840 --> 14:32.480
constantly.

14:32.480 --> 14:34.100
The essay also talks

14:34.100 --> 14:34.860
about this idea

14:34.860 --> 14:36.180
of the protagonist frame

14:36.180 --> 14:38.100
and cognitive relativity.

14:38.840 --> 14:40.100
This was a bit dense,

14:40.200 --> 14:41.060
but I think I got it.

14:41.280 --> 14:42.080
Let's unpack it.

14:42.180 --> 14:43.100
It's basically saying

14:43.100 --> 14:44.200
that to function,

14:44.980 --> 14:46.420
we have to assume

14:46.420 --> 14:48.140
a stable world, right?

14:48.180 --> 14:49.780
We have to see ourselves

14:49.780 --> 14:50.760
as the protagonist

14:50.760 --> 14:52.380
in a coherent story.

14:52.600 --> 14:52.880
Yes.

14:53.380 --> 14:54.080
Humans need

14:54.080 --> 14:55.080
a frame of reference.

14:55.620 --> 14:56.500
We can't process

14:56.500 --> 14:57.380
every perspective

14:57.380 --> 14:58.000
in the universe

14:58.000 --> 14:58.760
simultaneously.

14:58.980 --> 14:59.900
We just freeze.

14:59.900 --> 15:01.740
So we use heuristics,

15:01.920 --> 15:02.880
mental shortcuts

15:02.880 --> 15:04.940
to stabilize our world.

15:05.040 --> 15:06.200
To make life manageable.

15:06.420 --> 15:07.200
The essay mentions

15:07.200 --> 15:08.060
two big ones,

15:08.560 --> 15:09.400
cooperative intent

15:09.400 --> 15:10.340
and chunking.

15:10.420 --> 15:12.100
Okay, cooperative intent.

15:12.280 --> 15:13.320
This is the coffee shop

15:13.320 --> 15:14.000
example, right?

15:14.020 --> 15:14.300
Right.

15:14.480 --> 15:15.140
When you walk

15:15.140 --> 15:16.060
into a coffee shop,

15:16.140 --> 15:17.240
you assume the barista

15:17.240 --> 15:18.780
is not trying to poison you.

15:18.980 --> 15:20.100
A pretty safe assumption

15:20.100 --> 15:20.740
most days.

15:20.840 --> 15:21.780
You assume the person

15:21.780 --> 15:22.660
in line behind you

15:22.660 --> 15:23.620
isn't going to stab you.

15:23.880 --> 15:25.220
You assume a baseline

15:25.220 --> 15:26.020
of cooperation.

15:26.640 --> 15:27.480
We are all just here

15:27.480 --> 15:28.260
to get coffee.

15:28.700 --> 15:29.780
This saves energy.

15:30.100 --> 15:31.060
I don't have to treat

15:31.060 --> 15:32.520
every interaction

15:32.520 --> 15:33.720
as a combat scenario.

15:33.880 --> 15:34.380
I don't have to be

15:34.380 --> 15:35.140
a secret agent

15:35.140 --> 15:36.360
just to get a latte.

15:36.640 --> 15:36.980
Exactly.

15:37.200 --> 15:38.120
It lowers the metabolic

15:38.120 --> 15:39.080
cost of living.

15:39.760 --> 15:41.520
But constant polemic

15:41.520 --> 15:43.380
destroys that heuristic.

15:43.720 --> 15:44.780
It teaches you

15:44.780 --> 15:45.640
that everyone

15:45.640 --> 15:46.580
is an enemy

15:46.580 --> 15:47.220
or at least

15:47.220 --> 15:48.220
a potential one.

15:48.720 --> 15:49.760
If my feed tells me

15:49.760 --> 15:51.140
that every CEO

15:51.140 --> 15:52.100
is a psychopath,

15:52.780 --> 15:53.880
every politician

15:53.880 --> 15:54.600
is a traitor,

15:55.320 --> 15:55.940
every neighbor

15:55.940 --> 15:56.880
who votes differently

15:56.880 --> 15:58.400
is a moral monster.

15:58.400 --> 15:59.500
Then you lose

15:59.500 --> 16:00.120
the heuristic

16:00.120 --> 16:01.360
of cooperative intent,

16:01.740 --> 16:02.680
you enter a state

16:02.680 --> 16:04.220
of generalized suspicion,

16:04.600 --> 16:05.660
you have to vet

16:05.660 --> 16:06.680
every interaction

16:06.680 --> 16:07.740
for treachery.

16:07.800 --> 16:09.060
So now I'm in the coffee shop

16:09.060 --> 16:09.640
and I'm thinking,

16:10.180 --> 16:11.700
is this barista

16:11.700 --> 16:13.500
signaling a political stance

16:13.500 --> 16:14.420
I disagree with?

16:14.560 --> 16:14.920
Mm-hmm.

16:14.920 --> 16:15.940
Is the logo

16:15.940 --> 16:17.500
on that person's laptop

16:17.500 --> 16:18.420
a sign that they're

16:18.420 --> 16:19.400
a bad person?

16:19.480 --> 16:21.040
Is this email a trap?

16:21.140 --> 16:21.900
It's exhausting.

16:22.180 --> 16:23.600
It is metabolically expensive.

16:23.600 --> 16:24.860
Your brain has to work

16:24.860 --> 16:25.880
ten times as hard

16:25.880 --> 16:26.820
because it has to treat

16:26.820 --> 16:27.740
every interaction

16:27.740 --> 16:28.880
as a potential threat.

16:29.200 --> 16:30.580
You are burning glucose

16:30.580 --> 16:32.240
just trying to buy a muffin.

16:32.440 --> 16:33.720
And it makes you miserable.

16:33.900 --> 16:34.300
For sure.

16:34.420 --> 16:35.120
And then chunking.

16:35.400 --> 16:36.920
That's breaking big problems

16:36.920 --> 16:37.680
into small,

16:37.840 --> 16:38.900
manageable pieces, right?

16:39.360 --> 16:39.680
Yes.

16:39.960 --> 16:41.080
To solve a problem,

16:41.280 --> 16:41.860
you chunk it.

16:42.360 --> 16:43.480
I need to fix the car.

16:43.860 --> 16:44.400
Chunk one.

16:44.660 --> 16:45.200
Open hood.

16:45.720 --> 16:46.360
Chunk two.

16:47.120 --> 16:47.680
Check oil.

16:48.620 --> 16:49.180
Chunk three.

16:50.020 --> 16:51.000
Realize I know nothing

16:51.000 --> 16:51.640
about cars

16:51.640 --> 16:52.720
and call a mechanic.

16:53.140 --> 16:53.480
Right.

16:53.800 --> 16:54.540
But it's a process.

16:54.780 --> 16:55.420
It's a process.

16:55.760 --> 16:56.560
But systemic,

16:56.840 --> 16:57.860
polemical critique

16:57.860 --> 16:59.280
often argues that

16:59.280 --> 17:00.920
everything is wrong

17:00.920 --> 17:01.640
everywhere,

17:01.960 --> 17:02.640
all at once.

17:02.780 --> 17:04.120
The whole system is rotten.

17:04.640 --> 17:05.700
Burn it all down.

17:06.000 --> 17:06.480
Exactly.

17:06.740 --> 17:07.160
And look,

17:07.340 --> 17:08.680
sometimes the system is rotten.

17:09.020 --> 17:09.920
But if the whole system

17:09.920 --> 17:10.320
is rotten,

17:10.420 --> 17:11.500
you can't chunk it?

17:11.640 --> 17:12.560
There's no first step.

17:12.680 --> 17:13.600
Where you even start?

17:13.780 --> 17:15.160
You can't fix the oil

17:15.160 --> 17:16.060
if the problem is

17:16.060 --> 17:17.240
the universe is unjust.

17:17.240 --> 17:18.180
If the problem is

17:18.180 --> 17:19.540
capitalism or the West

17:19.540 --> 17:20.620
or human nature,

17:21.400 --> 17:22.620
where do you put the wrench?

17:22.620 --> 17:23.780
You can't start.

17:24.000 --> 17:24.840
It breaks our ability

17:24.840 --> 17:25.940
to tackle problems,

17:26.280 --> 17:27.420
which leads to paralysis.

17:28.000 --> 17:28.860
We just sit there

17:28.860 --> 17:29.540
doom-scrolling

17:29.540 --> 17:30.420
because the problems

17:30.420 --> 17:31.680
feel too big to touch.

17:32.040 --> 17:32.820
And that paralysis

17:32.820 --> 17:33.740
is a form of

17:33.740 --> 17:34.560
cognitive shutdown.

17:35.080 --> 17:36.180
There was another concept

17:36.180 --> 17:36.840
in this section

17:36.840 --> 17:37.280
that I found

17:37.280 --> 17:38.300
really illuminating.

17:38.760 --> 17:39.740
Predictive processing

17:39.740 --> 17:41.640
and chronic prediction error.

17:41.900 --> 17:42.700
This sounded like

17:42.700 --> 17:43.780
sci-fi brain stuff,

17:44.040 --> 17:44.780
like something out of

17:44.780 --> 17:45.900
a Neil Stephenson novel.

17:45.900 --> 17:47.260
It's the cutting edge

17:47.260 --> 17:48.420
of cognitive science.

17:48.680 --> 17:49.480
But the idea

17:49.480 --> 17:50.740
is actually simple.

17:51.520 --> 17:52.420
The theory is that

17:52.420 --> 17:53.800
the brain is basically

17:53.800 --> 17:54.960
a prediction engine.

17:55.380 --> 17:56.180
It wants to guess

17:56.180 --> 17:57.080
what happens next

17:57.080 --> 17:58.600
so it can conserve energy.

17:58.860 --> 17:59.820
Okay, that makes sense.

18:00.060 --> 18:00.960
If things are predictable,

18:01.300 --> 18:02.020
I can relax.

18:02.240 --> 18:03.260
When you are surprised,

18:03.460 --> 18:04.540
that's a prediction error.

18:04.860 --> 18:05.460
And your brain

18:05.460 --> 18:06.340
has to scramble

18:06.340 --> 18:07.720
to update its model

18:07.720 --> 18:08.400
of the world.

18:08.640 --> 18:09.960
Surprise equals stress.

18:10.200 --> 18:12.380
Surprise equals metabolic cost.

18:12.740 --> 18:14.120
If I walk into this room

18:14.120 --> 18:15.020
and there is a tiger,

18:15.520 --> 18:16.820
my brain has to do

18:16.820 --> 18:18.100
a massive amount of work

18:18.100 --> 18:19.740
to recalibrate reality.

18:20.520 --> 18:22.040
High frequency polemic

18:22.040 --> 18:22.880
creates a state

18:22.880 --> 18:24.440
of chronic surprise.

18:25.260 --> 18:26.000
You won't believe

18:26.000 --> 18:26.800
what they did.

18:27.600 --> 18:28.460
Shocking betrayal.

18:29.420 --> 18:30.560
Unprecedented disaster.

18:30.920 --> 18:31.600
Every headline

18:31.600 --> 18:32.660
is a tiger in the room.

18:32.900 --> 18:33.840
It keeps the brain

18:33.840 --> 18:34.400
in a state

18:34.400 --> 18:36.020
of constant recalibration.

18:36.020 --> 18:37.440
You are burning energy

18:37.440 --> 18:38.940
just trying to orient yourself

18:38.940 --> 18:39.400
in a world

18:39.400 --> 18:40.220
that keeps shifting

18:40.220 --> 18:41.040
under your feet.

18:41.340 --> 18:42.660
You never get to rest

18:42.660 --> 18:43.820
in a stable prediction.

18:44.120 --> 18:45.360
And the author links this

18:45.360 --> 18:46.760
to the design of our apps,

18:47.120 --> 18:47.560
calling it

18:47.560 --> 18:49.440
simulated collegiality,

18:49.860 --> 18:51.240
which is such a perfect

18:51.240 --> 18:52.440
cutting phrase.

18:52.820 --> 18:53.220
It is.

18:53.320 --> 18:54.520
It just nails it.

18:54.900 --> 18:55.960
Think about a modern

18:55.960 --> 18:57.320
social media platform.

18:58.000 --> 18:59.020
It looks friendly.

18:59.620 --> 19:00.460
Soft colors,

19:00.800 --> 19:01.720
rounded corners,

19:02.080 --> 19:02.760
prompts like

19:02.760 --> 19:04.020
what's on your mind,

19:04.460 --> 19:05.400
share with friends.

19:05.400 --> 19:07.440
It simulates a college campus

19:07.440 --> 19:08.380
or a living room.

19:08.940 --> 19:10.380
It's designed to feel

19:10.380 --> 19:11.440
safe and cozy.

19:11.840 --> 19:12.920
But underneath,

19:12.920 --> 19:15.280
it is a hostile architecture.

19:16.160 --> 19:18.040
It has opaque algorithms

19:18.040 --> 19:19.380
that hide your posts

19:19.380 --> 19:20.200
from your friends.

19:20.420 --> 19:21.960
It has data extraction

19:21.960 --> 19:23.140
that sells your behavior.

19:23.520 --> 19:24.740
And it has incentives

19:24.740 --> 19:26.200
that reward rage

19:26.200 --> 19:26.900
and conflict.

19:27.300 --> 19:28.340
It's a casino

19:28.340 --> 19:29.600
that looks like a playground.

19:29.920 --> 19:31.240
So it smiles at you

19:31.240 --> 19:32.320
while it picks your pocket

19:32.320 --> 19:33.720
and punches you in the gut.

19:33.920 --> 19:35.120
And that dissonance,

19:35.260 --> 19:36.020
the gap between

19:36.020 --> 19:37.120
the friendly interface

19:37.120 --> 19:38.720
and the hostile mechanic,

19:39.220 --> 19:40.180
forces the user

19:40.180 --> 19:41.040
into a state

19:41.040 --> 19:42.580
of tiring vigilance.

19:43.240 --> 19:43.860
You never know

19:43.860 --> 19:44.340
if the tool

19:44.340 --> 19:44.900
is your friend

19:44.900 --> 19:45.620
or your enemy.

19:46.160 --> 19:46.880
That uncertainty

19:46.880 --> 19:47.920
is exhausting.

19:48.440 --> 19:49.240
Okay, so at this point,

19:49.300 --> 19:50.900
I'm feeling pretty convinced

19:50.900 --> 19:51.620
that we should all

19:51.620 --> 19:52.380
just shut up,

19:52.680 --> 19:53.400
move to a cabin,

19:53.560 --> 19:54.380
and never complain

19:54.380 --> 19:55.620
about anything ever again.

19:55.740 --> 19:55.980
Right.

19:56.040 --> 19:56.460
The temptation

19:56.460 --> 19:57.340
is to just

19:57.340 --> 19:58.300
check out completely.

19:58.300 --> 19:59.400
If complaining

19:59.400 --> 20:00.700
destroys my brain

20:00.700 --> 20:01.580
and solves nothing,

20:01.760 --> 20:02.480
why do it?

20:02.580 --> 20:03.340
Let's all just go

20:03.340 --> 20:04.000
touch grass

20:04.000 --> 20:04.600
and be quiet.

20:05.060 --> 20:06.580
And that is exactly

20:06.580 --> 20:07.880
the nihilistic trap

20:07.880 --> 20:08.740
the essay has

20:08.740 --> 20:09.740
to warn us against.

20:09.940 --> 20:10.800
It's a really

20:10.800 --> 20:11.600
important turn.

20:12.120 --> 20:12.860
It brings us

20:12.860 --> 20:13.680
to part three,

20:14.220 --> 20:15.980
the infrastructural exception.

20:16.400 --> 20:17.160
Because if we just

20:17.160 --> 20:18.180
stop critiquing,

20:18.980 --> 20:19.520
we're essentially

20:19.520 --> 20:21.080
letting the bad guys win,

20:21.200 --> 20:21.400
right?

20:21.420 --> 20:22.640
If I stop complaining

20:22.640 --> 20:23.660
about the algorithm,

20:23.880 --> 20:24.520
the algorithm

20:24.520 --> 20:25.940
just keeps exploiting me.

20:26.000 --> 20:26.440
Worse,

20:26.440 --> 20:27.540
you let yourself

20:27.540 --> 20:28.240
be captured.

20:28.780 --> 20:29.920
The author introduces

20:29.920 --> 20:30.540
the concept

20:30.540 --> 20:31.760
of infrastructural

20:31.760 --> 20:32.580
subsumption.

20:32.780 --> 20:33.300
Subsumption?

20:33.400 --> 20:33.800
It sounds like

20:33.800 --> 20:34.760
something from a horror movie.

20:35.160 --> 20:37.200
The blob subsumes the town.

20:37.460 --> 20:38.620
It's not far off.

20:38.900 --> 20:39.640
It refers to

20:39.640 --> 20:40.520
when a platform

20:40.520 --> 20:41.820
doesn't just provide a tool,

20:42.000 --> 20:42.940
but it swallows

20:42.940 --> 20:44.140
an entire domain

20:44.140 --> 20:44.920
of activity.

20:45.180 --> 20:46.120
Okay, give me an example.

20:46.260 --> 20:47.580
Think about video creators.

20:48.200 --> 20:49.180
YouTube isn't just

20:49.180 --> 20:50.580
a tool for them.

20:50.700 --> 20:51.480
It is the market.

20:51.780 --> 20:53.160
It is the distribution network.

20:53.360 --> 20:54.160
It is the bank.

20:54.240 --> 20:55.620
It is the entire ecosystem.

20:55.620 --> 20:56.740
It's the whole world.

20:56.740 --> 20:58.120
If you are a creator

20:58.120 --> 20:59.820
and you aren't on YouTube,

21:00.120 --> 21:00.800
you effectively

21:00.800 --> 21:02.420
don't exist in that space.

21:02.460 --> 21:03.900
You can't just opt out

21:03.900 --> 21:04.680
without losing

21:04.680 --> 21:05.340
your livelihood.

21:05.620 --> 21:06.700
You are subsumed.

21:07.140 --> 21:08.000
You're digested

21:08.000 --> 21:08.700
by the system.

21:08.840 --> 21:09.360
Exactly.

21:09.920 --> 21:11.840
And in that specific scenario,

21:12.300 --> 21:13.320
the essay argues

21:13.320 --> 21:15.320
refusal is necessary.

21:16.200 --> 21:17.080
Polemic becomes

21:17.080 --> 21:18.480
a tool of last resort.

21:18.840 --> 21:19.540
This is the

21:19.540 --> 21:20.880
infrastructural exception.

21:21.060 --> 21:21.280
Yes.

21:21.720 --> 21:22.780
The essay isn't saying

21:22.780 --> 21:23.680
never complain.

21:23.680 --> 21:24.760
It's saying

21:24.760 --> 21:25.860
we need to distinguish

21:25.860 --> 21:27.300
between venting

21:27.300 --> 21:29.220
and boundary maintenance.

21:29.820 --> 21:30.500
When a system

21:30.500 --> 21:31.500
is trying to capture

21:31.500 --> 21:32.120
your labor

21:32.120 --> 21:33.100
and lock it up,

21:33.420 --> 21:34.540
you must critique it.

21:34.740 --> 21:35.600
There's this chilling

21:35.600 --> 21:36.760
phrase in the essay,

21:37.200 --> 21:37.840
contribution

21:37.840 --> 21:39.720
as extraction.

21:40.140 --> 21:41.360
This is critical

21:41.360 --> 21:42.700
for the AI era

21:42.700 --> 21:43.440
we're living in.

21:43.540 --> 21:44.460
In these systems,

21:44.660 --> 21:45.560
your usage,

21:45.840 --> 21:47.000
even your complaints,

21:47.400 --> 21:49.100
creates data

21:49.100 --> 21:50.300
that trains

21:50.300 --> 21:51.120
the system.

21:51.120 --> 21:51.440
Right.

21:51.540 --> 21:52.440
If I spend all day

21:52.440 --> 21:52.900
on Twitter

21:52.900 --> 21:53.980
arguing that Twitter

21:53.980 --> 21:54.640
is bad,

21:54.960 --> 21:55.840
I am generating

21:55.840 --> 21:56.900
engagement metrics

21:56.900 --> 21:57.780
that help Twitter

21:57.780 --> 21:58.600
sell ads.

21:58.940 --> 22:00.440
My rage is their product.

22:00.580 --> 22:01.560
And if you are using

22:01.560 --> 22:02.480
a coding assistant

22:02.480 --> 22:03.620
or a writing tool

22:03.620 --> 22:04.400
and you correct

22:04.400 --> 22:05.100
its mistakes,

22:05.640 --> 22:06.500
those corrections

22:06.500 --> 22:07.620
are training data

22:07.620 --> 22:08.800
for the next version

22:08.800 --> 22:09.620
of the model.

22:09.780 --> 22:10.900
You are optimizing

22:10.900 --> 22:11.520
the system

22:11.520 --> 22:12.340
through your labor.

22:12.480 --> 22:13.620
Unpaid optimization.

22:14.360 --> 22:15.320
I'm working

22:15.320 --> 22:16.140
for the machine

22:16.140 --> 22:16.800
for free

22:16.800 --> 22:17.840
while often paying

22:17.840 --> 22:18.420
a subscription

22:18.420 --> 22:19.620
to use the machine.

22:19.740 --> 22:20.540
That's infuriating.

22:20.540 --> 22:21.120
It is.

22:21.460 --> 22:22.620
But here's a trap.

22:23.060 --> 22:24.180
You improve the system

22:24.180 --> 22:25.180
but the owner

22:25.180 --> 22:26.600
locks those improvements

22:26.600 --> 22:28.400
behind a paywall

22:28.400 --> 22:29.660
or proprietary code.

22:30.140 --> 22:31.220
You build the castle

22:31.220 --> 22:32.460
but you aren't allowed

22:32.460 --> 22:33.120
to live in it.

22:33.740 --> 22:34.680
Your own insights

22:34.680 --> 22:35.880
are sold back to you.

22:36.340 --> 22:37.020
So in this case,

22:37.380 --> 22:38.740
polemic isn't just noise.

22:38.860 --> 22:39.600
It's what the author

22:39.600 --> 22:41.960
calls diagnostic refusal.

22:42.360 --> 22:43.260
It's hygiene.

22:43.500 --> 22:44.400
It's marking a boundary.

22:44.520 --> 22:45.440
It's a flare

22:45.440 --> 22:46.720
fired for a very

22:46.720 --> 22:47.780
specific reason.

22:47.780 --> 22:48.160
And it's saying,

22:48.400 --> 22:50.060
I see what you're doing.

22:50.220 --> 22:51.280
I see that this is

22:51.280 --> 22:52.060
not collaboration.

22:52.060 --> 22:53.120
This is capture.

22:53.360 --> 22:53.980
I will not be

22:53.980 --> 22:54.920
your unpaid intern.

22:55.240 --> 22:56.440
That is a valid

22:56.440 --> 22:58.260
necessary use of critique.

22:58.360 --> 22:59.180
Okay, so we have

22:59.180 --> 22:59.660
a problem.

23:00.220 --> 23:00.840
Polemic debt.

23:01.080 --> 23:01.880
We have the exception.

23:03.040 --> 23:04.200
Infrastructural defense.

23:05.080 --> 23:06.180
Now let's talk solutions.

23:06.900 --> 23:07.680
How do we argue

23:07.680 --> 23:08.900
without going bankrupt?

23:09.760 --> 23:11.060
The essay proposes

23:11.060 --> 23:13.100
disciplined refutation.

23:13.780 --> 23:14.420
This is about

23:14.420 --> 23:15.380
shifting critique

23:15.380 --> 23:16.780
from a default mode

23:16.780 --> 23:17.980
which is what we have now.

23:18.040 --> 23:18.900
Right, from a habit.

23:19.000 --> 23:20.320
To a clearing operation.

23:20.440 --> 23:21.280
A clearing operation.

23:21.400 --> 23:21.860
I like that.

23:21.920 --> 23:22.740
It sounds purposeful.

23:22.980 --> 23:24.200
Think of a construction site.

23:24.680 --> 23:25.640
Before you build a house,

23:25.860 --> 23:26.920
you have to clear the brush.

23:27.180 --> 23:28.000
You have to cut down

23:28.000 --> 23:28.920
the trees and pull up

23:28.920 --> 23:29.380
the stumps.

23:29.520 --> 23:30.180
That's critique.

23:30.500 --> 23:31.720
You clear the obstacles.

23:32.160 --> 23:33.300
It's necessary work.

23:33.360 --> 23:34.020
You can't build

23:34.020 --> 23:34.860
on a pile of junk.

23:35.620 --> 23:36.660
But you don't live

23:36.660 --> 23:37.740
in the clearing process.

23:38.160 --> 23:38.760
You don't spend

23:38.760 --> 23:39.340
your whole life

23:39.340 --> 23:40.060
chopping bushes.

23:40.220 --> 23:40.700
You clear,

23:40.880 --> 23:41.620
then you build.

23:41.620 --> 23:42.380
But online,

23:42.560 --> 23:43.440
we have people

23:43.440 --> 23:43.980
who just,

23:44.580 --> 23:46.760
they've professionalized

23:46.760 --> 23:47.520
the bush chopping.

23:47.660 --> 23:49.020
That's their entire identity.

23:49.280 --> 23:50.140
They are professional

23:50.140 --> 23:50.960
demolitionists

23:50.960 --> 23:51.540
in a world

23:51.540 --> 23:52.740
that needs architects.

23:52.960 --> 23:53.680
They are standing

23:53.680 --> 23:54.680
in a clear field,

23:54.900 --> 23:56.360
swinging axes at the air,

23:56.500 --> 23:57.100
wondering why

23:57.100 --> 23:58.580
no houses are getting built.

23:59.020 --> 23:59.660
So how do we

23:59.660 --> 24:00.420
become architects?

24:01.140 --> 24:02.260
The essay offers

24:02.260 --> 24:02.740
a couple of

24:02.740 --> 24:03.780
really cool strategies.

24:04.140 --> 24:05.180
The first one is

24:05.180 --> 24:07.340
emphematic critique.

24:08.260 --> 24:08.880
Now I had to

24:08.880 --> 24:09.600
look this word up.

24:09.680 --> 24:10.360
It sounds like something

24:10.360 --> 24:11.720
you'd need a prescription for.

24:11.920 --> 24:13.140
It comes from Aristotle.

24:13.700 --> 24:14.420
An enthymeme

24:14.420 --> 24:15.260
is an argument

24:15.260 --> 24:16.700
where one premise

24:16.700 --> 24:18.140
is left unstated

24:18.140 --> 24:19.660
because it's obvious

24:19.660 --> 24:20.640
to the audience.

24:20.940 --> 24:22.160
Give me the classic example.

24:22.460 --> 24:23.640
Socrates is a man,

24:23.920 --> 24:25.260
so Socrates is mortal.

24:26.060 --> 24:27.460
The missing premise is

24:27.460 --> 24:29.480
all men are mortal.

24:30.060 --> 24:31.080
You don't have to say it.

24:31.480 --> 24:32.780
The audience fills that in.

24:32.960 --> 24:34.240
It respects their intelligence.

24:34.700 --> 24:36.340
Okay, so how does that apply

24:36.340 --> 24:37.460
to saving the internet

24:37.460 --> 24:38.160
from itself?

24:38.160 --> 24:39.720
The author argues

24:39.720 --> 24:40.500
we should use this

24:40.500 --> 24:41.140
for critique.

24:41.640 --> 24:42.400
So instead of writing

24:42.400 --> 24:43.560
a 10-page rant

24:43.560 --> 24:45.560
about how the current system

24:45.560 --> 24:46.780
traps your data,

24:47.260 --> 24:48.380
the big manifesto,

24:48.540 --> 24:49.660
you simply build

24:49.660 --> 24:50.900
and release a tool

24:50.900 --> 24:53.140
that exports data cleanly.

24:53.220 --> 24:54.100
Here is a tool

24:54.100 --> 24:55.180
for data portability.

24:56.300 --> 24:56.820
That's it.

24:56.900 --> 24:58.380
By offering the solution,

24:58.780 --> 25:00.220
you imply the critique.

25:00.640 --> 25:02.220
The existence of the solution

25:02.220 --> 25:04.140
proves the problem exists.

25:04.300 --> 25:05.120
Here is a key.

25:05.120 --> 25:08.020
E implies you are in a prison,

25:08.640 --> 25:10.240
but you haven't triggered

25:10.240 --> 25:12.420
the defensive emotional reaction

25:12.420 --> 25:13.280
of a polemic.

25:13.360 --> 25:14.560
You sidestep the whole

25:14.560 --> 25:16.320
System 1 outrage cycle.

25:16.580 --> 25:17.900
It's critique

25:17.900 --> 25:19.620
as structural absence.

25:20.120 --> 25:21.460
You're letting the solution

25:21.460 --> 25:22.540
cast a shadow

25:22.540 --> 25:24.220
that reveals the shape

25:24.220 --> 25:24.940
of the problem.

25:25.140 --> 25:26.900
It is incredibly powerful.

25:27.280 --> 25:28.120
Twitter can argue

25:28.120 --> 25:29.100
with a manifesto.

25:29.320 --> 25:30.780
They can release a PR statement

25:30.780 --> 25:32.620
saying we value user freedom,

25:32.620 --> 25:34.020
but they can't argue

25:34.020 --> 25:35.280
with a tool that works.

25:35.460 --> 25:36.540
The tool changes

25:36.540 --> 25:37.900
the reality on the ground.

25:38.320 --> 25:39.260
It shifts the energy

25:39.260 --> 25:40.940
from fighting to solving,

25:41.420 --> 25:42.420
but the critical point

25:42.420 --> 25:43.360
remains intact.

25:43.620 --> 25:44.220
It's brilliant.

25:44.360 --> 25:45.340
It's a game changer

25:45.340 --> 25:46.780
if people actually adopt it.

25:46.860 --> 25:47.720
The second strategy

25:47.720 --> 25:48.960
is one of my favorite concepts

25:48.960 --> 25:49.780
from the Renaissance.

25:50.580 --> 25:51.160
Espresso Tura.

25:51.320 --> 25:53.440
Ah, Castileon is the courtier.

25:53.720 --> 25:54.340
A classic.

25:54.840 --> 25:55.820
The art of making

25:55.820 --> 25:57.760
the difficult look effortless.

25:57.760 --> 25:59.760
In the 16th century,

25:59.920 --> 26:00.740
it meant dancing

26:00.740 --> 26:01.800
or sword fighting

26:01.800 --> 26:03.040
or composing a poem

26:03.040 --> 26:03.600
on the spot

26:03.600 --> 26:04.740
without breaking a sweat.

26:05.240 --> 26:06.600
It meant looking cool

26:06.600 --> 26:07.620
while doing something

26:07.620 --> 26:08.640
incredibly hard.

26:08.820 --> 26:09.040
Right.

26:09.220 --> 26:10.000
No straining.

26:10.220 --> 26:11.520
And in 2026,

26:11.980 --> 26:12.920
the author argues,

26:13.360 --> 26:14.860
it means offering critique

26:14.860 --> 26:16.180
without the sweaty

26:16.180 --> 26:17.560
performance of outrage.

26:18.100 --> 26:18.940
Effortless critique.

26:19.320 --> 26:21.120
It's about signaling mastery.

26:21.580 --> 26:23.040
If you scream and yell

26:23.040 --> 26:24.260
and tear your hair out,

26:24.260 --> 26:25.440
you signal that

26:25.440 --> 26:26.160
you are threatened.

26:26.160 --> 26:27.440
You signal that

26:27.440 --> 26:28.120
you are losing.

26:28.580 --> 26:30.080
I am panic honking my horn

26:30.080 --> 26:30.720
because I don't know

26:30.720 --> 26:31.440
how to drive.

26:31.700 --> 26:32.180
Exactly.

26:32.660 --> 26:34.800
But if you calmly present

26:34.800 --> 26:36.260
a procedural solution,

26:36.540 --> 26:37.820
a better way of doing things,

26:38.200 --> 26:39.120
you signal that

26:39.120 --> 26:40.060
you are in control.

26:40.400 --> 26:41.540
You signal competence.

26:41.860 --> 26:43.620
It lowers the cognitive load

26:43.620 --> 26:44.420
on the audience.

26:44.640 --> 26:45.320
It's the difference

26:45.320 --> 26:46.560
between a panic driver

26:46.560 --> 26:47.560
honking their horn

26:47.560 --> 26:48.740
and a mechanic

26:48.740 --> 26:49.780
calmly handing you

26:49.780 --> 26:51.080
a replaced spark plug.

26:51.360 --> 26:52.240
Here's your problem.

26:52.500 --> 26:52.920
Fixed it.

26:53.560 --> 26:54.080
Exactly.

26:54.460 --> 26:55.840
When you see someone panic,

26:55.840 --> 26:56.540
you panic.

26:57.100 --> 26:58.560
When you see someone competent,

26:58.900 --> 26:59.580
you relax.

26:59.980 --> 27:00.680
You trust them.

27:00.840 --> 27:01.580
You follow them.

27:01.760 --> 27:02.800
And the author invokes

27:02.800 --> 27:03.900
Paul Firebend here,

27:04.180 --> 27:05.280
the philosopher of science,

27:05.440 --> 27:06.700
to argue for

27:06.700 --> 27:08.480
methodological pluralism.

27:08.840 --> 27:09.980
Which basically means

27:09.980 --> 27:11.540
use the right tool

27:11.540 --> 27:12.320
for the job.

27:12.580 --> 27:13.700
His famous line was

27:13.700 --> 27:14.700
anything goes.

27:14.880 --> 27:15.140
Right.

27:15.620 --> 27:16.260
Don't get stuck

27:16.260 --> 27:17.060
on one method.

27:17.340 --> 27:18.460
Sometimes you need a riot.

27:18.880 --> 27:20.160
Sometimes you need a polemic

27:20.160 --> 27:21.180
to wake people up.

27:21.180 --> 27:22.260
But sometimes,

27:22.640 --> 27:24.020
and arguably more often

27:24.020 --> 27:24.620
right now,

27:25.020 --> 27:26.240
you need a blueprint.

27:26.660 --> 27:27.780
You need spread the Torah.

27:28.000 --> 27:28.760
You need to build

27:28.760 --> 27:29.500
the alternative.

27:29.880 --> 27:30.940
We need an ecology

27:30.940 --> 27:32.000
of argument,

27:32.280 --> 27:33.500
not just a monoculture

27:33.500 --> 27:34.220
of anger.

27:34.620 --> 27:35.540
Well said.

27:35.680 --> 27:36.580
Okay, so that covers

27:36.580 --> 27:37.440
the human side.

27:37.960 --> 27:38.660
And honestly,

27:38.820 --> 27:40.220
if the essay stopped there,

27:40.400 --> 27:41.420
it would be a great

27:41.420 --> 27:42.420
insightful essay

27:42.420 --> 27:43.140
about psychology

27:43.800 --> 27:44.600
and politics.

27:44.740 --> 27:45.320
It would.

27:45.800 --> 27:46.640
But it doesn't

27:46.640 --> 27:47.280
stop there.

27:47.320 --> 27:48.420
No, it pivots hard.

27:48.420 --> 27:49.560
A technical pivot.

27:49.740 --> 27:50.820
It pivots to

27:50.820 --> 27:52.280
text editors.

27:52.980 --> 27:53.460
Specifically,

27:53.880 --> 27:54.140
Vim.

27:54.700 --> 27:55.640
Which, as we said,

27:55.700 --> 27:56.840
is the part that makes you go,

27:57.080 --> 27:57.980
wait, what?

27:58.340 --> 27:59.080
I have to admit,

27:59.180 --> 28:00.320
when I first read the outline,

28:00.460 --> 28:00.900
I laughed.

28:01.260 --> 28:01.960
We're talking about

28:01.960 --> 28:03.180
saving modern discourse,

28:03.680 --> 28:04.420
saving our brains

28:04.420 --> 28:05.560
from cortisol poisoning,

28:05.860 --> 28:06.820
and the solution

28:06.820 --> 28:08.340
is a command line tool

28:08.340 --> 28:09.560
from 1976.

28:10.120 --> 28:11.500
It seems absurd, doesn't it?

28:11.500 --> 28:11.840
It feels like

28:11.840 --> 28:12.900
a total non-sequitur.

28:12.920 --> 28:13.860
It feels like saying,

28:13.860 --> 28:15.260
to fix climate change,

28:15.400 --> 28:16.020
everyone needs

28:16.020 --> 28:16.800
to learn to knit.

28:17.060 --> 28:18.040
But stick with me.

28:18.400 --> 28:19.420
Remember the connection.

28:20.360 --> 28:21.620
Cognitive continuity.

28:22.760 --> 28:23.900
The essay argues

28:23.900 --> 28:25.100
that just as constant

28:25.100 --> 28:26.600
outrage breaks our focus,

28:27.100 --> 28:28.420
bad software tools

28:28.420 --> 28:29.720
break our flow.

28:30.200 --> 28:30.880
They introduce

28:30.880 --> 28:32.060
tiny points of friction

28:32.060 --> 28:33.620
that bleed our attention away.

28:34.080 --> 28:34.940
So let's unpack this

28:34.940 --> 28:35.560
for the listeners

28:35.560 --> 28:36.980
who might not be coders.

28:37.360 --> 28:38.080
What is Vim?

28:38.400 --> 28:40.020
Vim is a text editor.

28:40.540 --> 28:42.200
But unlike Microsoft Word

28:42.200 --> 28:43.200
or Google Docs,

28:43.300 --> 28:44.140
it's modal.

28:44.540 --> 28:44.960
Modal.

28:45.080 --> 28:45.760
What does that mean?

28:45.980 --> 28:46.860
It means the keyboard

28:46.860 --> 28:47.980
has different modes.

28:48.600 --> 28:49.340
In one mode,

28:49.620 --> 28:50.940
the keys type letters,

28:51.100 --> 28:51.520
like normal.

28:51.720 --> 28:53.000
We call that insert mode.

28:53.140 --> 28:54.000
Okay, simple enough.

28:54.100 --> 28:55.060
But in the other mode,

28:55.260 --> 28:55.820
normal mode,

28:56.300 --> 28:57.780
the keys become commands.

28:58.500 --> 28:59.880
D deletes a line.

29:00.180 --> 29:01.540
W moves the cursor

29:01.540 --> 29:02.520
forward a word.

29:02.980 --> 29:04.180
J moves down a line.

29:04.180 --> 29:05.360
Your whole keyboard

29:05.360 --> 29:06.500
becomes a verb.

29:07.040 --> 29:07.600
So you're not reaching

29:07.600 --> 29:08.080
for the mouse

29:08.080 --> 29:08.980
every two seconds

29:08.980 --> 29:09.780
to click on a button?

29:09.960 --> 29:11.180
You never touch the mouse.

29:11.500 --> 29:11.760
Ever.

29:11.760 --> 29:13.300
And the author argues

29:13.300 --> 29:14.780
this creates muscle memory

29:14.780 --> 29:16.500
as cognitive economy.

29:16.720 --> 29:18.240
Okay, visualize this for us.

29:18.320 --> 29:18.520
Uh-huh.

29:18.740 --> 29:20.500
Why is the mouse bad?

29:21.500 --> 29:22.560
I like my mouse.

29:22.820 --> 29:23.800
Imagine you were writing

29:23.800 --> 29:25.200
a really complex thought.

29:25.440 --> 29:26.360
You are in the zone.

29:26.700 --> 29:27.740
The words are flowing.

29:28.180 --> 29:28.900
Suddenly you realize

29:28.900 --> 29:29.920
you need to move a paragraph

29:29.920 --> 29:31.100
from the bottom of the page

29:31.100 --> 29:31.620
to the top.

29:31.820 --> 29:32.100
Okay.

29:32.320 --> 29:32.920
In Word,

29:33.040 --> 29:33.680
what do you do?

29:34.080 --> 29:35.560
Describe the physical actions.

29:35.560 --> 29:37.140
I stop typing.

29:37.540 --> 29:38.600
I lift my hand

29:38.600 --> 29:39.260
from the keyboard.

29:39.600 --> 29:40.860
I find the mouse.

29:41.360 --> 29:42.240
I locate the cursor

29:42.240 --> 29:42.980
on the screen.

29:43.260 --> 29:44.280
I scroll down.

29:44.840 --> 29:45.860
I highlight the text.

29:46.100 --> 29:46.640
I right-click

29:46.640 --> 29:48.500
or hit Command-C.

29:49.000 --> 29:49.720
No, cut.

29:50.260 --> 29:51.200
So Command-X.

29:51.800 --> 29:52.540
Then I scroll up.

29:52.980 --> 29:53.700
I find the right spot.

29:54.120 --> 29:54.300
Click.

29:54.820 --> 29:55.320
Command-V.

29:55.840 --> 29:57.080
That whole process

29:57.080 --> 29:57.780
took maybe

29:57.780 --> 29:59.580
five, six seconds.

29:59.840 --> 30:00.140
Mm-hmm.

30:00.140 --> 30:01.440
But in those five seconds,

30:01.560 --> 30:02.840
you had to switch your brain

30:02.840 --> 30:04.900
from thinking about the idea

30:04.900 --> 30:06.740
to navigating the interface.

30:07.140 --> 30:07.940
You had to become

30:07.940 --> 30:09.560
a pilot of the software.

30:09.860 --> 30:10.820
It's a micro-interruption.

30:11.000 --> 30:11.900
It's a context switch.

30:12.100 --> 30:13.280
It's a cognitive leak.

30:13.660 --> 30:14.440
Your idea,

30:14.660 --> 30:15.420
the fragile thing

30:15.420 --> 30:16.440
you were holding in your head,

30:16.980 --> 30:18.220
leaked out during the scroll.

30:19.080 --> 30:19.500
In Vim,

30:19.580 --> 30:20.560
once you know the language,

30:20.680 --> 30:21.540
your fingers just do.

30:21.620 --> 30:21.840
You think,

30:22.080 --> 30:22.680
move paragraph.

30:23.040 --> 30:24.340
Your fingers hit three keys

30:24.340 --> 30:26.260
and it happens instantly.

30:26.460 --> 30:27.320
You didn't look away.

30:27.320 --> 30:28.340
You didn't stop thinking

30:28.340 --> 30:29.100
about the sentence.

30:29.500 --> 30:30.680
The interface disappears.

30:31.000 --> 30:32.120
It gets out of your way.

30:32.520 --> 30:34.060
You aren't manipulating a tool.

30:34.060 --> 30:35.440
You are manipulating the text

30:35.440 --> 30:37.300
directly at the speed of thought.

30:37.520 --> 30:38.580
The essay calls this

30:38.580 --> 30:39.940
the universal buffer,

30:40.160 --> 30:41.340
this idea that text

30:41.340 --> 30:42.460
is the core element.

30:42.980 --> 30:43.260
Yes.

30:44.140 --> 30:45.340
In the Unix tradition,

30:45.620 --> 30:47.340
text is a first-class object.

30:47.980 --> 30:48.740
It's the water

30:48.740 --> 30:50.020
that flows through all the pipes.

30:50.520 --> 30:51.520
You can move text

30:51.520 --> 30:52.440
from a file

30:52.440 --> 30:53.740
to a program

30:53.740 --> 30:55.860
back to another file

30:55.860 --> 30:56.880
seamlessly.

30:57.540 --> 30:58.340
Contrast that

30:58.340 --> 30:59.380
with modern apps.

30:59.600 --> 31:00.580
The regressions,

31:00.800 --> 31:01.820
as the author calls them.

31:01.820 --> 31:03.340
Modern apps

31:03.340 --> 31:04.320
are walled gardens.

31:04.540 --> 31:04.940
They don't want

31:04.940 --> 31:05.840
to talk to each other.

31:05.840 --> 31:08.060
The clipboard fragmentation point

31:08.060 --> 31:09.240
really annoyed me

31:09.240 --> 31:10.720
because it's so true.

31:10.980 --> 31:12.280
I tried to copy something

31:12.280 --> 31:13.040
from a PDF,

31:13.820 --> 31:14.960
paste it into a spreadsheet.

31:15.120 --> 31:16.000
And it's a disaster.

31:16.200 --> 31:16.720
It breaks.

31:16.880 --> 31:18.200
The formatting explodes.

31:18.840 --> 31:20.620
Or it pastes as an image.

31:20.880 --> 31:22.100
Or the app just says,

31:22.480 --> 31:23.480
you cannot paste here.

31:23.700 --> 31:25.500
The apps are actively fighting

31:25.500 --> 31:26.180
your attempts

31:26.180 --> 31:27.240
to move information.

31:27.660 --> 31:28.460
It feels like the apps

31:28.460 --> 31:29.100
are fighting me.

31:29.180 --> 31:29.280
Why?

31:29.280 --> 31:31.220
Because they're sandboxed.

31:31.460 --> 31:32.500
Security sandboxing

31:32.500 --> 31:33.400
is good for safety.

31:33.640 --> 31:34.720
It stops viruses.

31:35.120 --> 31:37.040
But it kills composability.

31:37.320 --> 31:37.900
It prevents you

31:37.900 --> 31:39.280
from chaining tools together.

31:39.760 --> 31:40.720
The data is trapped

31:40.720 --> 31:41.540
inside the app.

31:41.760 --> 31:43.000
The company wants to keep you

31:43.000 --> 31:43.860
in their ecosystem.

31:44.140 --> 31:44.660
And search.

31:45.060 --> 31:46.100
The essay roasts

31:46.100 --> 31:46.860
modern search.

31:47.280 --> 31:47.940
It does.

31:48.680 --> 31:50.300
Modern search is curated.

31:51.020 --> 31:52.080
An algorithm decides

31:52.080 --> 31:52.880
what you want to see.

31:53.280 --> 31:55.020
You search your own email

31:55.020 --> 31:55.920
for invoice,

31:55.920 --> 31:57.520
and it shows you

31:57.520 --> 31:58.560
what it thinks

31:58.560 --> 31:59.240
is important,

31:59.580 --> 32:00.200
not necessarily

32:00.200 --> 32:01.020
what is there

32:01.020 --> 32:02.020
chronologically.

32:02.340 --> 32:03.320
It's like a librarian

32:03.320 --> 32:04.300
who hides books

32:04.300 --> 32:04.880
they don't think

32:04.880 --> 32:05.540
you should read,

32:05.860 --> 32:06.540
even though you own

32:06.540 --> 32:06.980
the library.

32:07.160 --> 32:07.860
That's a perfect way

32:07.860 --> 32:08.340
to put it.

32:08.900 --> 32:09.660
Unix search,

32:09.840 --> 32:11.120
like a tool called grep,

32:11.320 --> 32:12.560
is an archaeologist

32:12.560 --> 32:13.460
with a flashlight.

32:14.060 --> 32:14.980
It interrogates

32:14.980 --> 32:15.880
the raw data.

32:16.340 --> 32:17.240
It finds exactly

32:17.240 --> 32:18.020
what is there,

32:18.160 --> 32:19.200
whether it's pretty or not.

32:19.600 --> 32:20.280
It respects

32:20.280 --> 32:21.120
your intelligence.

32:21.540 --> 32:22.240
One treats you

32:22.240 --> 32:23.040
like a consumer

32:23.040 --> 32:24.220
whose preferences

32:24.220 --> 32:25.300
must be managed.

32:25.740 --> 32:26.720
The other treats you

32:26.720 --> 32:27.320
like a builder

32:27.320 --> 32:28.880
who needs raw materials.

32:29.060 --> 32:29.540
Exactly.

32:29.860 --> 32:30.540
And then there's

32:30.540 --> 32:31.180
Biobu.

32:31.900 --> 32:32.840
This was new to me.

32:33.040 --> 32:34.040
Biobu, what is it?

32:34.200 --> 32:36.000
It's a terminal multiplexer,

32:36.380 --> 32:37.220
but think of it

32:37.220 --> 32:39.060
as cognitive persistence,

32:39.780 --> 32:40.860
a tool for it.

32:40.960 --> 32:41.440
Resistence.

32:41.460 --> 32:42.880
We all have setup fatigue.

32:43.080 --> 32:43.720
Every morning,

32:44.080 --> 32:44.960
you open your laptop,

32:45.220 --> 32:46.000
you open your browser,

32:46.220 --> 32:47.040
your 10 tabs,

32:47.120 --> 32:48.200
you open your documents,

32:48.600 --> 32:49.700
you arrange your windows

32:49.700 --> 32:50.580
just so you get

32:50.580 --> 32:51.800
your Spotify playlist.

32:51.940 --> 32:52.560
You have to build

32:52.560 --> 32:53.440
your house every day

32:53.440 --> 32:54.460
before you can live in it.

32:54.560 --> 32:55.140
It's a ritual

32:55.140 --> 32:56.000
that takes like

32:56.000 --> 32:57.280
5, 10 minutes.

32:57.740 --> 32:59.280
And if the computer crashes

32:59.280 --> 33:00.040
or it decides

33:00.040 --> 33:00.900
to update overnight,

33:01.180 --> 33:02.040
you lose it all.

33:02.220 --> 33:03.000
You have to rebuild

33:03.000 --> 33:03.700
from memory.

33:03.880 --> 33:04.820
It's so frustrating.

33:05.140 --> 33:05.860
With Biobu

33:05.860 --> 33:06.840
running on a server,

33:07.020 --> 33:07.660
you can detect

33:07.660 --> 33:08.360
from your session.

33:08.560 --> 33:09.160
You can close

33:09.160 --> 33:09.680
your laptop.

33:10.120 --> 33:10.740
You can fly

33:10.740 --> 33:11.580
across the world.

33:11.700 --> 33:12.040
You can buy

33:12.040 --> 33:13.760
a cheap $200 laptop

33:13.760 --> 33:15.120
in a cafe in Tokyo.

33:15.440 --> 33:16.620
You open a terminal

33:16.620 --> 33:17.920
and SSH in,

33:18.120 --> 33:19.260
and your cursor

33:19.260 --> 33:20.120
is blinking

33:20.120 --> 33:21.820
in the exact same spot

33:21.820 --> 33:22.460
you left it.

33:22.560 --> 33:23.960
Your files are open,

33:24.440 --> 33:25.820
your windows are arranged,

33:26.080 --> 33:27.920
your music is paused

33:27.920 --> 33:29.480
at the same second.

33:29.480 --> 33:30.500
So the workspace

33:30.500 --> 33:31.220
is permanent.

33:31.540 --> 33:32.300
It's not tied

33:32.300 --> 33:33.420
to the physical machine.

33:33.640 --> 33:34.060
It supports

33:34.060 --> 33:35.300
cognitive context.

33:35.800 --> 33:36.400
You don't have to

33:36.400 --> 33:37.160
waste energy

33:37.160 --> 33:38.160
setting up your brain

33:38.160 --> 33:38.780
every morning.

33:39.240 --> 33:40.020
The environment

33:40.020 --> 33:41.400
is waiting for you

33:41.400 --> 33:43.040
exactly as you left it.

33:43.180 --> 33:44.760
It respects your attention.

33:45.140 --> 33:45.900
This all builds

33:45.900 --> 33:47.300
to a really big distinction

33:47.300 --> 33:49.260
in part 6 of the essay,

33:49.800 --> 33:50.540
Builder Culture

33:50.540 --> 33:51.680
versus User Culture.

33:52.060 --> 33:53.420
This is the heart

33:53.420 --> 33:54.640
of the technical argument.

33:54.800 --> 33:55.320
The latency

33:55.320 --> 33:56.340
of tool availability.

33:56.780 --> 33:56.960
Yeah.

33:57.220 --> 33:58.040
I love this concept.

33:58.180 --> 33:58.780
Let's break it down

33:58.780 --> 33:59.620
using an analogy.

33:59.800 --> 34:00.020
Okay.

34:00.520 --> 34:01.560
Imagine you rely

34:01.560 --> 34:02.100
on the bus

34:02.100 --> 34:02.840
to get to work.

34:03.060 --> 34:04.060
If the bus is late

34:04.060 --> 34:05.180
or if the bus route

34:05.180 --> 34:06.300
doesn't go to your new office,

34:06.380 --> 34:07.080
what do you do?

34:07.360 --> 34:07.880
I wait.

34:08.420 --> 34:09.480
Or I complain

34:09.480 --> 34:10.460
to the city council.

34:11.040 --> 34:12.120
Maybe I sign a petition.

34:12.120 --> 34:13.380
You wait.

34:13.900 --> 34:15.040
You are dependent.

34:15.880 --> 34:16.860
There is a latency,

34:17.460 --> 34:18.500
a delay between

34:18.500 --> 34:19.500
your problem,

34:19.680 --> 34:20.620
I need to get there,

34:20.840 --> 34:21.980
and the solution,

34:22.880 --> 34:23.780
the bus moves.

34:24.180 --> 34:25.000
That latency

34:25.000 --> 34:25.700
is controlled

34:25.700 --> 34:26.760
by a third party.

34:27.480 --> 34:28.820
That is User Culture.

34:29.740 --> 34:30.360
I am waiting

34:30.360 --> 34:31.460
for Apple or Google

34:31.460 --> 34:32.760
to update the app

34:32.760 --> 34:33.920
to fix the bug

34:33.920 --> 34:34.660
that annoys me.

34:34.840 --> 34:36.220
I file a feedback report

34:36.220 --> 34:36.700
and hope.

34:36.940 --> 34:37.400
Exactly.

34:37.620 --> 34:38.480
You are a passenger.

34:38.820 --> 34:39.460
You are passive.

34:39.880 --> 34:40.920
But in Builder Culture.

34:41.060 --> 34:41.960
In Builder Culture.

34:42.400 --> 34:43.200
Using tools

34:43.200 --> 34:43.960
like Python,

34:44.200 --> 34:44.980
Shell Scripts,

34:45.000 --> 34:45.580
or Lisp,

34:46.020 --> 34:46.960
you have a car.

34:47.260 --> 34:47.760
Or better yet,

34:47.800 --> 34:48.500
you have a garage

34:48.500 --> 34:49.760
full of parts and tools.

34:50.280 --> 34:51.240
You have a problem.

34:51.400 --> 34:51.980
You fix it.

34:52.340 --> 34:53.100
You write a script.

34:53.340 --> 34:53.760
You automate

34:53.760 --> 34:54.680
the tedious thing.

34:54.800 --> 34:55.480
You fix it.

34:55.640 --> 34:55.980
Now,

34:56.300 --> 34:56.960
this afternoon.

34:57.180 --> 34:58.460
You close the gap yourself.

34:58.700 --> 34:59.640
There is no latency.

34:59.980 --> 35:01.820
That is epistemic agency.

35:02.440 --> 35:03.320
You have the power

35:03.320 --> 35:03.900
to perform

35:03.900 --> 35:04.900
local optimization.

35:05.500 --> 35:06.300
You don't have to wait

35:06.300 --> 35:06.880
for the feature

35:06.880 --> 35:07.540
to be profitable

35:07.540 --> 35:08.100
for Google.

35:08.260 --> 35:09.160
You just build it

35:09.160 --> 35:10.140
because you need it.

35:10.260 --> 35:11.240
But modern platforms

35:11.240 --> 35:12.480
are actively hostile

35:12.480 --> 35:13.240
to this, right?

35:13.320 --> 35:13.740
They want us

35:13.740 --> 35:14.500
to be consumers,

35:14.660 --> 35:15.180
not builders.

35:15.360 --> 35:15.800
They want us

35:15.800 --> 35:16.740
to stay on the bus.

35:17.180 --> 35:19.040
They want legible users.

35:19.700 --> 35:20.440
Users who fit

35:20.440 --> 35:21.940
into the database rows.

35:22.580 --> 35:23.360
Users who click

35:23.360 --> 35:24.020
the buttons

35:24.020 --> 35:25.160
provided in the order

35:25.160 --> 35:25.920
they expect.

35:26.300 --> 35:27.080
And if you start

35:27.080 --> 35:28.360
writing your own scripts

35:28.360 --> 35:30.500
to interact with their platform,

35:30.680 --> 35:32.280
you are scraping

35:32.280 --> 35:33.420
or hacking.

35:33.980 --> 35:34.460
You're breaking

35:34.460 --> 35:35.400
the terms of service

35:35.400 --> 35:36.820
by trying to be efficient

35:36.820 --> 35:38.060
or create a workflow

35:38.060 --> 35:39.420
that works better for you.

35:39.780 --> 35:40.360
And this leads

35:40.360 --> 35:41.700
to a loss of composability.

35:42.060 --> 35:42.360
Yeah.

35:42.520 --> 35:43.460
The Unix philosophy

35:43.460 --> 35:44.800
was simple, right?

35:45.000 --> 35:45.300
Very.

35:45.880 --> 35:46.980
Write small programs

35:46.980 --> 35:48.500
that do one thing well.

35:48.720 --> 35:49.200
Then what?

35:49.480 --> 35:50.160
Write programs

35:50.160 --> 35:51.000
to work together.

35:51.640 --> 35:52.660
And write programs

35:52.660 --> 35:54.100
to handle text streams

35:54.100 --> 35:55.100
because text

35:55.100 --> 35:56.720
is the universal interface.

35:56.720 --> 35:57.980
Like Lego bricks.

35:58.640 --> 35:59.620
Each brick is simple,

35:59.940 --> 36:00.600
but you can build

36:00.600 --> 36:01.640
a starship out of them.

36:01.920 --> 36:02.640
Modern apps

36:02.640 --> 36:04.140
are glued together statues.

36:04.600 --> 36:05.440
You can look at them,

36:05.540 --> 36:06.660
but you can't take them apart

36:06.660 --> 36:07.800
and build something new.

36:08.380 --> 36:09.340
The essay argues

36:09.340 --> 36:10.320
we need to recover

36:10.320 --> 36:11.240
that composability.

36:11.720 --> 36:12.280
We need to be able

36:12.280 --> 36:13.540
to chain our tools together

36:13.540 --> 36:14.800
to create our own workflows.

36:15.400 --> 36:16.760
So, putting it all together

36:16.760 --> 36:17.600
in Part 7,

36:18.100 --> 36:19.300
the essay outlines

36:19.300 --> 36:20.820
Design Principles

36:20.820 --> 36:21.760
for Resilience.

36:22.660 --> 36:24.020
If we want to escape

36:24.020 --> 36:24.960
the polemic debt

36:24.960 --> 36:26.240
and the app trap,

36:26.720 --> 36:27.200
what do we need

36:27.200 --> 36:27.720
our tools

36:27.720 --> 36:28.940
and platforms to do?

36:29.300 --> 36:31.180
First, interoperability.

36:32.000 --> 36:32.920
Data must be portable.

36:33.480 --> 36:34.300
If you can't get

36:34.300 --> 36:35.040
your data out

36:35.040 --> 36:35.840
in a clean,

36:36.100 --> 36:36.960
open format,

36:37.300 --> 36:37.700
JSON,

36:38.420 --> 36:39.100
CSV,

36:39.580 --> 36:40.320
plain text,

36:40.760 --> 36:41.540
you are captured.

36:41.960 --> 36:43.000
That's the baseline.

36:43.320 --> 36:44.020
Rule number one,

36:44.700 --> 36:45.660
don't use a tool

36:45.660 --> 36:46.180
that holds

36:46.180 --> 36:47.100
your thinking hostage.

36:47.780 --> 36:48.420
What's next?

36:48.540 --> 36:49.720
Cognitive sustainability.

36:50.180 --> 36:51.140
I love that phrase.

36:51.300 --> 36:52.260
Interfaces should

36:52.260 --> 36:53.280
respect attention.

36:53.700 --> 36:55.200
No infinite scrolls.

36:55.200 --> 36:57.060
No algorithmic interruption.

36:57.580 --> 36:59.600
No red notification badges

36:59.600 --> 37:01.220
designed to trigger anxiety.

37:01.480 --> 37:02.500
The tool should be passive

37:02.500 --> 37:03.800
until you act on it.

37:04.020 --> 37:04.760
It should be a hammer

37:04.760 --> 37:05.880
waiting on the bench,

37:06.000 --> 37:06.920
not a slot machine

37:06.920 --> 37:08.160
screaming for your coins.

37:08.560 --> 37:09.260
Beautifully put.

37:09.640 --> 37:10.200
And finally,

37:10.360 --> 37:11.280
governance transparency.

37:12.080 --> 37:12.620
We need to see

37:12.620 --> 37:13.560
the rules of the system

37:13.560 --> 37:14.040
we're in.

37:14.480 --> 37:15.680
And reciprocity.

37:15.940 --> 37:16.460
Reciprocity.

37:16.640 --> 37:17.780
If I create value

37:17.780 --> 37:18.580
for the platform

37:18.580 --> 37:19.800
through my content,

37:20.040 --> 37:20.660
my corrections,

37:20.960 --> 37:22.060
my community building,

37:22.060 --> 37:23.300
the platform

37:23.300 --> 37:24.100
should recognize

37:24.100 --> 37:24.900
that value,

37:25.180 --> 37:26.340
not just extract it.

37:26.460 --> 37:27.060
It feels like

37:27.060 --> 37:27.980
the SA is trying

37:27.980 --> 37:28.740
to build a bridge

37:28.740 --> 37:29.860
between the ethos

37:29.860 --> 37:31.080
of the 1970s

37:31.080 --> 37:31.700
and the problems

37:31.700 --> 37:32.760
of the 2030s.

37:32.760 --> 37:33.460
That's a great way

37:33.460 --> 37:33.860
to put it.

37:33.940 --> 37:35.280
It's taking the sovereignty

37:35.280 --> 37:36.300
of the early

37:36.300 --> 37:37.020
hacker culture

37:37.020 --> 37:37.920
and applying it

37:37.920 --> 37:39.300
to the attention crisis

37:39.300 --> 37:40.520
of the AI age.

37:40.880 --> 37:42.200
So let's synthesize this.

37:42.660 --> 37:43.420
We started with

37:43.420 --> 37:44.540
online outrage

37:44.540 --> 37:46.280
and we ended

37:46.280 --> 37:47.960
with terminal multiplexers.

37:48.380 --> 37:50.060
What is the through line?

37:50.060 --> 37:51.820
What connects these two

37:51.820 --> 37:53.700
seemingly opposite worlds?

37:54.280 --> 37:54.700
Conservation.

37:55.260 --> 37:55.780
Conservation.

37:56.040 --> 37:56.980
Polemic debt

37:56.980 --> 37:58.260
is about conservation.

37:58.940 --> 37:59.800
We need to conserve

37:59.800 --> 38:01.560
our severity gradients

38:01.560 --> 38:02.740
so that when we scream

38:02.740 --> 38:03.340
fire,

38:03.540 --> 38:04.820
people actually look.

38:04.960 --> 38:05.760
We need to conserve

38:05.760 --> 38:07.200
our attentional bandwidth

38:07.200 --> 38:08.520
so we can think

38:08.520 --> 38:09.500
clearly enough

38:09.500 --> 38:10.600
to build solutions,

38:10.840 --> 38:12.360
not just react

38:12.360 --> 38:13.200
to provocations.

38:13.500 --> 38:14.680
And we need to conserve

38:14.680 --> 38:16.960
our intellectual continuity

38:16.960 --> 38:18.600
by using tools

38:18.600 --> 38:20.140
that don't trap us

38:20.140 --> 38:21.760
or fragment our focus.

38:22.020 --> 38:23.300
It's about not wasting

38:23.300 --> 38:24.920
our most precious resources,

38:25.520 --> 38:26.100
our focus

38:26.100 --> 38:26.980
and our credibility.

38:27.180 --> 38:27.700
Precisely.

38:27.880 --> 38:28.480
If we spend

38:28.480 --> 38:29.400
all our credibility

38:29.400 --> 38:30.520
on Twitter beefs

38:30.520 --> 38:31.280
and all our focus

38:31.280 --> 38:31.840
on fighting

38:31.840 --> 38:33.140
with bad user interfaces,

38:33.440 --> 38:34.580
we have nothing left

38:34.580 --> 38:35.080
in the tank

38:35.080 --> 38:35.980
to actually build

38:35.980 --> 38:36.460
the future.

38:36.580 --> 38:37.840
That is a powerful takeaway.

38:38.600 --> 38:39.320
Stop spending,

38:39.780 --> 38:40.340
start saving,

38:40.680 --> 38:41.280
start building.

38:41.660 --> 38:42.380
And start ignoring

38:42.380 --> 38:43.480
the noise that doesn't matter,

38:43.560 --> 38:44.320
which is most of it.

38:44.380 --> 38:45.020
Which brings us

38:45.020 --> 38:45.960
to our final thought.

38:46.040 --> 38:46.600
I want to go back

38:46.600 --> 38:47.380
to Sprezzatura.

38:47.780 --> 38:49.020
The art of nonchalance.

38:49.400 --> 38:50.100
I'm imagining

38:50.100 --> 38:51.160
a digital life

38:51.160 --> 38:52.680
lived with Sprezzatura.

38:53.580 --> 38:54.860
You aren't frantically

38:54.860 --> 38:56.560
reacting to every notification.

38:57.020 --> 38:58.020
You aren't getting engaged

38:58.020 --> 38:59.240
in every flame war.

38:59.580 --> 39:00.840
You're using tools

39:00.840 --> 39:01.780
that are quiet,

39:02.400 --> 39:02.880
powerful,

39:03.300 --> 39:03.980
and persistent.

39:04.240 --> 39:05.280
Tools that you command,

39:05.440 --> 39:06.540
not the other way around.

39:06.680 --> 39:07.260
You're building

39:07.260 --> 39:08.100
your own scripts.

39:08.500 --> 39:09.100
You're solving

39:09.100 --> 39:09.900
your own problems.

39:10.100 --> 39:10.820
You're moving

39:10.820 --> 39:11.680
with a kind of

39:11.680 --> 39:13.580
quiet confidence.

39:13.640 --> 39:15.140
It's a very attractive image,

39:15.140 --> 39:16.620
the digital courtier.

39:17.580 --> 39:18.100
Calm,

39:18.440 --> 39:18.880
effective,

39:19.240 --> 39:20.180
and unbothered.

39:20.280 --> 39:20.600
It is.

39:21.020 --> 39:22.420
So here is the question

39:22.420 --> 39:23.120
for you,

39:23.240 --> 39:23.640
the listener.

39:24.700 --> 39:25.540
What would it look like

39:25.540 --> 39:26.540
for you to move

39:26.540 --> 39:27.780
through the digital world

39:27.780 --> 39:30.000
with cultivated nonchalance?

39:30.880 --> 39:32.400
Are you a frantic user

39:32.400 --> 39:33.480
waiting for an update

39:33.480 --> 39:34.900
and screaming at the screen?

39:35.120 --> 39:36.200
Or are you a builder

39:36.200 --> 39:37.880
regulating your own outrage,

39:38.040 --> 39:39.040
writing your own rules,

39:39.140 --> 39:40.560
and refusing to be interrupted?

39:40.940 --> 39:42.160
Is true autonomy

39:42.160 --> 39:43.180
just the ability

39:43.180 --> 39:44.240
to stay focused?

39:44.240 --> 39:45.540
I think it might be

39:45.540 --> 39:46.660
the ultimate superpower

39:46.660 --> 39:47.900
for the 21st century.

39:48.080 --> 39:48.720
I think so, too.

39:49.360 --> 39:50.440
That's something to think about

39:50.440 --> 39:51.240
the next time you reach

39:51.240 --> 39:51.820
for your phone.

39:52.540 --> 39:53.620
Thanks for diving in with us.

39:53.860 --> 39:54.640
Until next time.

39:54.900 --> 39:55.760
See you in the deep end.

